{"title_page": "May 2", "text_new": "{{Redirect|2 May|the Romanian village|2 Mai}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n*[[1194]] &ndash; King [[Richard I of England]] gives [[Portsmouth]] its first [[Royal Charter]].\n*[[1230]] &ndash; [[William de Braose (died 1230)|William de Braose]] is hanged by Prince [[Llywelyn the Great]].\n*[[1335]] &ndash; [[Otto, Duke of Austria|Otto the Merry]], Duke of Austria, becomes [[Duchy of Carinthia|Duke of Carinthia]].\n*[[1536]] &ndash; [[Anne Boleyn]], [[Queen consort|Queen of England]], is arrested and imprisoned on charges of [[adultery]], [[incest]], [[treason]] and [[witchcraft]].\n*[[1559]] &ndash; [[John Knox]] returns from exile to Scotland to become the leader of the nascent [[Scottish Reformation]].\n*[[1568]] &ndash; [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], escapes from [[Loch Leven Castle]].\n*[[1611]] &ndash; The [[King James Version]] of the [[Bible]] is published for the first time in London, England, by printer Robert Barker.\n*[[1625]] &ndash; [[Afonso Mendes]], appointed by [[Pope Gregory XV]] as [[Latin Patriarchate of Ethiopia]], arrives at [[Beilul]] from [[Goa]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Travels_of_the_Jesuits_in_Ethiopia.html?id=dtYWAAAAQAAJ&page=PA225 |title=The Travels of the Jesuits in Ethiopia |last=Telles |first=Balthazar |date=1710 |publisher=J. Knapton |pages=225}}</ref>\n*[[1670]] &ndash; King [[Charles II of England]] grants a permanent charter to the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] to open up the [[fur trade]] in North America.\n*[[1672]] &ndash; [[John Maitland, 1st Duke of Lauderdale|John Maitland]] becomes [[Duke of Lauderdale]] and [[Earl of March]].\n*[[1808]] &ndash; Outbreak of the [[Peninsular War]]: The people of [[Madrid]] [[Dos de Mayo Uprising|rise up in rebellion]] against French occupation. [[Francisco de Goya]] later memorializes this event in his painting ''[[The Second of May 1808]]''.\n*[[1812]] &ndash; The [[Siege of Cuautla]] during the [[Mexican War of Independence]] ends with both sides claiming victory after Mexican rebels under [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Morelos y Pav\u00f3n]] abandon the city after 72 days under siege by royalist Spanish troops under [[F\u00e9lix Mar\u00eda Calleja]].\n*[[1816]] &ndash; Marriage of [[Leopold I of Belgium|L\u00e9opold of Saxe-Coburg]] and [[Princess Charlotte of Wales]].\n*[[1829]] &ndash; After anchoring nearby, Captain [[Charles Fremantle]] of {{HMS|Challenger|1826|6}}, declares the [[Swan River Colony]] in Australia.\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: [[Stonewall Jackson]] is wounded by friendly fire while returning to camp after reconnoitering during the [[Battle of Chancellorsville]]. He succumbs to [[pneumonia]] eight days later.\n*[[1866]] &ndash; [[Peru]]vian defenders fight off the Spanish fleet at the [[Battle of Callao]].\n*[[1876]] &ndash; The [[April Uprising]] breaks out in [[Ottoman Bulgaria]].\n*[[1879]] &ndash; The [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]] is founded in Madrid by [[Pablo Iglesias Posse|Pablo Iglesias]].\n*[[1885]] &ndash; [[Cree]] and [[Assiniboine]] warriors win the [[Battle of Cut Knife]], their largest victory over Canadian forces during the [[North-West Rebellion]].\n*[[1889]] &ndash; [[Menelik II]], Emperor of [[Ethiopia]], signs the [[Treaty of Wuchale]], giving Italy control over [[Eritrea]].\n*[[1906]] &ndash; Closing ceremony of the [[1906 Intercalated Games|Intercalated Games]] in [[Athens]], Greece.\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[General Motors]] acquires the [[Chevrolet Motor Company]] of [[Delaware]].\n*[[1920]] &ndash; The first game of the [[Negro National League (1920\u201331)|Negro National League baseball]] is played in [[Indianapolis]].\n*[[1933]] &ndash; Germany's independent labor unions are replaced by the [[German Labour Front]].\n*[[1941]] &ndash; Following the ''[[1941 Iraqi coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]]'' against [[Iraq]] Crown Prince [['Abd al-Ilah]] earlier that year, the United Kingdom launches the [[Anglo-Iraqi War]] to restore him to power.\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: The [[Soviet Union]] announces the [[Battle of Berlin|fall of Berlin]].\n*  1945   &ndash; World War II: The [[surrender of Caserta]] comes into effect, by which German troops in Italy cease fighting.\n*  1945   &ndash; World War II: The US 82nd Airborne Division liberates [[W\u00f6bbelin concentration camp]] finding 1000 dead prisoners, most of whom starved to death.\n*  1945   &ndash; World War II: A [[Death marches (Holocaust)#Dachau to the Austrian border|death march]] from [[Dachau concentration camp|Dachau]] to the Austrian border is halted by the segregated, all-[[Nisei]] [[442nd Infantry Regiment (United States)#522nd Field Artillery Battalion|522nd Field Artillery Battalion]] of the U.S. Army in southern Bavaria, saving several hundred prisoners.\n*[[1952]] &ndash; The world's first ever [[jet airliner]], the [[De Havilland Comet]] 1 makes its maiden flight, from London to [[Johannesburg]].\n*[[1955]] &ndash; [[Tennessee Williams]] wins the [[Pulitzer Prize for Drama]] for ''[[Cat on a Hot Tin Roof]]''.\n*[[1963]] &ndash; [[Berthold Seliger]] launches a rocket with three stages and a maximum flight altitude of more than 100 kilometres near [[Cuxhaven]]. It is the only [[sounding rocket]] developed in Germany.\n*[[1964]] &ndash; [[Vietnam War]]: [[Attack on USNS Card|An explosion]] sinks the American aircraft carrier USS ''Card'' while it is docked at Saigon. Two Viet Cong [[Frogman|combat swimmers]] had placed explosives on the ship's hull. She is raised and returned to service less than seven months later.\n*  1964   &ndash; [[First ascent]] of [[Shishapangma]], the fourteenth highest [[mountain]] in the world and the lowest of the [[Eight-thousander]]s.\n*[[1969]] &ndash; The British ocean liner ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'' departs on her maiden voyage to New York City.\n*[[1972]] &ndash; In the early morning hours a fire breaks out at the [[Sunshine Mine (Idaho)|Sunshine Mine]] located between Kellogg and Wallace, Idaho, killing 91 workers.\n*[[1982]] &ndash; [[Falklands War]]: The British [[nuclear submarine]] {{HMS|Conqueror|S48|6}} sinks the [[Argentina|Argentine]] cruiser [[ARA General Belgrano|ARA ''General Belgrano'']].\n*[[1986]] &ndash; [[Chernobyl disaster]]: The City of [[Chernobyl]] is evacuated six days after the disaster.\n*[[1989]] &ndash; [[Cold War]]: Hungary begins [[Removal of Hungary's border fence with Austria|dismantling its border fence with Austria]], which allows a number of [[East Germany|East Germans]] to defect.\n*[[1994]] &ndash; A bus [[Poland bus disaster of 1994|crashes]] in [[Gda\u0144sk|Gda\u0144sk, Poland]] killing 32 people.\n*[[1995]] &ndash; During the [[Croatian War of Independence]], the [[Army of the Republic of Serb Krajina]] [[Zagreb rocket attacks|fires cluster bombs]] at [[Zagreb]], killing seven and wounding over 175 civilians.\n*[[1998]] &ndash; The [[European Central Bank]] is founded in [[Brussels]] in order to define and execute the [[European Union]]'s monetary policy.\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[Panamanian general election, 1999]]: [[Mireya Moscoso]] becomes the first woman to be elected [[President of Panama]].\n*[[2000]] &ndash; President [[Bill Clinton]] announces that accurate [[Global Positioning System|GPS]] access would no longer be restricted to the [[United States Armed Forces|United States military]].\n*[[2004]] &ndash; The [[Yelwa massacre]] concludes. It began on 4 February 2004 when armed Muslims killed 78 Christians at Yelwa. In response, about 630 Muslims were killed by Christians on May 2nd.\n*[[2008]] &ndash; [[Cyclone Nargis]] makes landfall in [[Burma]] killing over 138,000 people and leaving millions of people homeless.\n*  2008   &ndash; [[Chait\u00e9n (volcano)|Chait\u00e9n Volcano]] begins erupting in [[Chile]], forcing the evacuation of more than 4,500 people.\n*[[2011]] &ndash; [[Osama bin Laden]], the suspected mastermind behind the [[September 11 attacks]] and the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]]'s most wanted man, is [[Death of Osama bin Laden|killed]] by the [[United States Navy SEALs|United States special forces]] in [[Abbottabad]], Pakistan.\n*  2011   &ndash; An [[2011 E. coli O104:H4 outbreak|E. coli outbreak]] strikes Europe, mostly in Germany, leaving more than 30 people dead and many others sick from the [[bacteria]] outbreak.\n*[[2012]] &ndash; A [[pastel]] version of ''[[The Scream]]'', by Norwegian painter [[Edvard Munch]], sells for $120 million in a New York City auction, setting a new world record for a work of art at auction.\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[2014 Badakhshan mudslides|Two mudslides]] in [[Badakhshan]], [[Afghanistan]], leave up to 2,500 people missing.\n*[[2018]] &ndash; [[Basque nationalism|Basque separatist]] terrorist band [[ETA (separatist group)|ETA]] announces its dissolution and ceasing of all activities.\n\n==Births==\n*[[1360]] &ndash; [[Yongle Emperor]] of China (d. 1424)\n*[[1402]] &ndash; [[Eleanor of Aragon, Queen of Portugal]] (d. 1445)\n*[[1451]] &ndash; [[Ren\u00e9 II, Duke of Lorraine]] (d. 1508)\n*[[1458]] &ndash; [[Eleanor of Viseu]] (d. 1525)\n*[[1476]] &ndash; [[Charles I, Duke of M\u00fcnsterberg-Oels]], Count of Kladsko, Governor of Bohemia and Silesia (d. 1536)\n*[[1533]] &ndash; [[Philip II, Duke of Brunswick-Grubenhagen]] (d. 1596)\n*[[1551]] &ndash; [[William Camden]], English historian and topographer (d. 1623)\n*[[1567]] &ndash; [[Sebald de Weert]], Dutch captain, vice-admiral of the Dutch East India Company (d. 1603)\n*[[1579]] &ndash; [[Tokugawa Hidetada]], Japanese sh\u014dgun (d. 1632)\n*[[1601]] &ndash; [[Athanasius Kircher]], German priest and scholar (d. 1680)\n*[[1660]] &ndash; [[Alessandro Scarlatti]], Italian composer (d. 1725)\n*[[1695]] &ndash; [[Giovanni Niccol\u00f2 Servandoni]], Italian-French painter and architect (d. 1766)\n*[[1702]] &ndash; [[Friedrich Christoph Oetinger]], German theologian and theosopher (d. 1782)\n*[[1707]] &ndash; [[Jean-Baptiste Barri\u00e8re]], French cellist and composer (d. 1747)\n*[[1729]] &ndash; [[Catherine the Great]] of Russia (d. 1796)\n*[[1737]] &ndash; [[William Petty, 2nd Earl of Shelburne]], Irish-English politician, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (d. 1805)\n*[[1740]] &ndash; [[Elias Boudinot]], American lawyer and politician, 10th [[President of the Continental Congress]] (d. 1821)\n*[[1750]] &ndash; [[John Andr\u00e9]], English soldier and spy (d. 1780)\n*[[1752]] &ndash; [[Ludwig August Lebrun]], German [[oboe]] player and composer (d. 1790)\n*[[1754]] &ndash; [[Vicente Mart\u00edn y Soler]], Spanish composer (d. 1806)\n*[[1772]] &ndash; [[Novalis]], German author and poet (d. 1801)\n*[[1773]] &ndash; [[Henrik Steffens]], Norwegian philosopher and poet (d. 1845)\n*[[1797]] &ndash; [[Abraham Pineo Gesner]], Canadian physician and geologist (d. 1864)\n*[[1802]] &ndash; [[Heinrich Gustav Magnus]], German chemist and physicist (d. 1870)\n*[[1806]] &ndash; [[Catherine Labour\u00e9]], French nun and saint (d. 1876)\n*[[1810]] &ndash; [[Hans Christian Lumbye]], Danish composer and conductor (d. 1874)\n*[[1813]] &ndash; [[Caroline Leigh Gascoigne]], English novelist and poet (d. 1883)<ref name=\"Thomas1915\">{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Joseph|title=Lippincott's Pronouncing Dictionary of Biography and Mythology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RnwVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1080|edition=Public domain|year=1915|publisher=J. B. Lippincott Company|page=1080}}</ref>\n*[[1815]] &ndash; [[William Buell Richards]], Canadian lawyer and judge, 1st [[Chief Justice of Canada]] (d. 1889)\n*[[1822]] &ndash; [[Jane Miller Thengberg]], Scottish-Swedish governess and educator (d. 1902)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sok.riksarkivet.se/Sbl/Mobil/Artikel/9352|title=Jane Miller Thengberg|website=sok.riksarkivet.se|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref>\n*[[1828]] &ndash; [[D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Charnay]], French archaeologist and photographer (d. 1915)\n*[[1830]] &ndash; [[Otto Staudinger]], German entomologist and author (d. 1900)\n*[[1843]] &ndash; [[Elijah McCoy]], Canadian-American engineer (d. 1929)\n*[[1859]] &ndash; [[Jerome K. Jerome]], English author and playwright (d. 1927)\n*[[1860]] &ndash; [[John Scott Haldane]], Scottish physiologist, physician, and academic (d. 1936)\n*  1860   &ndash; [[Theodor Herzl]], Austro-Hungarian Zionist philosopher, journalist and author (d. 1904)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[Clyde Fitch]], American playwright (d. 1909)\n*[[1867]] &ndash; [[Giuseppe Morello]], Italian-American mobster (d. 1930)\n*[[1873]] &ndash; [[Jurgis Baltru\u0161aitis]], Lithuanian poet, critic, and translator (d. 1944)\n*[[1879]] &ndash; [[James F. Byrnes]], American stenographer and politician, 49th [[United States Secretary of State]] (d. 1972)\n*[[1880]] &ndash; [[Bill Horr]], American football player, discus thrower, and coach (d. 1955)\n*[[1882]] &ndash; [[Isabel Gonz\u00e1lez]], Puerto Rican activist who helped pave the way for Puerto Ricans' American citizenship (d. 1971)\n*[[1885]] &ndash; [[Hedda Hopper]], American actress and gossip columnist (d. 1966)\n*[[1886]] &ndash; [[Gottfried Benn]], German author and poet (d. 1956)\n*[[1887]] &ndash; [[Vernon and Irene Castle|Vernon Castle]], English-American dancer (d. 1918)\n*  1887   &ndash; [[Eddie Collins]], American baseball player and manager (d. 1951)\n*[[1889]] &ndash; [[Ki Hajar Dewantara]], Indonesian philosopher, academic, and politician (d. 1959)\n*[[1890]] &ndash; [[E. E. Smith]], American engineer and author (d. 1965)\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[Manfred von Richthofen]], German captain and pilot (d. 1918)\n*[[1894]] &ndash; [[Norma Talmadge]], leading US actress of the silent era (d. 1957)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Basinger |first1=Jeanine |title=Silent Stars |date=2000 |publisher=Wesleyan University Press. |isbn=0-8195-6451-6 |page=[https://archive.org/details/silentstars00basi/page/181 181] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/silentstars00basi/page/181 }}</ref>\n