story/index.php/May_2 Today in Canadian History]\n\n{{months}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:May 02}}\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:May]]\n", "name_user": "Googgoollman7777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBirths:Removed unnecessary links.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/May_2"}
{"title_page": "Barnes & Noble", "text_new": "{{short description|American bookseller and retailer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{stack begin}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Barnes & Noble, Inc.\n| logo = Barnes & Noble logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| ISIN = US0677741094\n| predecessor = Arthur Hinds & Company\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1886}} (as Arthur Hinds & Company)<br>[[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| founders = Charles M. Barnes<br />William Barnes<br />G. Clifford Noble<br />[[Leonard Riggio]]<ref name=\"water_stones\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/07/books/barnes-noble-sale.html |last=Alter  |first=Alexandra |last2=Hsu  |first2=Tiffany |date=June 7, 2019 |title=Barnes & Noble Is Sold to Hedge Fund After a Tumultuous Year |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"imprint\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/05/07/476931295/barnes-noble-founder-retires-leaving-his-imprint-on-bookstores-history |date=May 7, 2016 |title=Barnes & Noble Founder Retires, Leaving His Imprint On Bookstore's History |work=[[NPR]]|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| location_city = New York City, New York\n| location_country = U.S.\n| locations = 627 retail stores<br>({{as of|2019|3|7|df=US}})<ref name=\"fiscal2019-3rdqtr\">{{cite press release |url=http://investors.barnesandnobleinc.com/news-releases/news-release-details/barnes-noble-reports-fiscal-2019-third-quarter-results |title=Barnes & Noble Reports Fiscal 2019 Third Quarter Results |work=Barnes & Noble |date=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n| key_people = Leonard Riggio ([[Chairperson|Chairman]]),<br>[[James Daunt]] ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| products = [[Barnes & Noble Nook|Nook]]<br>[[SparkNotes]]\n| brands = '''Barnes & Noble Booksellers'''<br />'''Nook Digital, LLC'''<br />'''Sterling Publishing'''\n| revenue = {{decrease}} [[US$]] 3.552 billion (FY 2019)\n| operating_income = {{increase}} US$ 38.596 million (FY 2019)\n| net_income = {{decrease}} US$ 3.769 million (FY 2019)\n| assets = {{steady}} US$ 1.705 billion (FY 2019)\n| equity = {{steady}} US$ 444.497 million (FY 2019)\n| num_employees = 24,000 (2019) \n| slogan = \n| owner = Public company / Leonard Riggio - largest shareholder (11.8%)\n| parent = [[Elliott Management Corporation]]\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/}} (corporate site)<br />{{URL|http://www.barnesandnoble.com/}} (consumer site)<br /> {{URL|http://www.nook.com/}} (consumer site)\n| footnotes= <ref>{{cite web|url=https://wallmine.com/nyse/bks|date=July 29, 2019|title=Barnes & Noble|work=wallmine|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{stack end}}\n'''Barnes & Noble, Inc.''', is an American bookseller. It is a [[Fortune 1000]] company and the bookseller with the largest number of retail outlets in the United States. As of March 7, 2019, the company operates 627 retail stores in all 50 [[U.S. states]].<ref name=\"fiscal2019-3rdqtr\" /> In August 2019, [[Elliott Management Corporation]] acquired the company.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190807005399/en/Elliott-Completes-Acquisition-Barnes-Noble | title=Elliott Completes Acquisition of Barnes & Noble | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBarnes & Noble operates mainly through its Barnes & Noble Booksellers chain of [[bookstore]]s. The company's headquarters are at 122 [[Fifth Avenue]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/sponsorship/sponsorships_national/donations_national.html|title=National Sponsorships and Donations|accessdate=January 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121101559/http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/sponsorship/sponsorships_national/donations_national.html|archive-date=January 21, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter a series of mergers and bankruptcies in the American bookstore industry since the 1990s, Barnes & Noble stands alone as the United States' largest national bookstore chain.<ref name=\"wp\">{{cite web|last=DePillis|first=Lydia|title=Barnes & Noble's troubles don't show why bookstores are doomed. They show how they'll survive.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/07/10/barnes-nobles-troubles-dont-show-why-its-doomed-they-show-how-it-survives/|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 30, 2013|date=July 10, 2013|quote=it's now the only national bookstore chain in the country}}</ref><ref name=\"bw\">{{cite web|last=Townsend |first=Matt |title=Bookstores Not Dead Yet as Riggio Bets on Barnes & Noble |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2013-07-10/bookstores-not-dead-yet-as-riggio-bets-on-barnes-and-noble |work=Bloomberg Businessweek |accessdate=October 30, 2013 |date=July 10, 2013 |quote=the last national bookstore chain |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130916111734/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2013-07-10/bookstores-not-dead-yet-as-riggio-bets-on-barnes-and-noble |archivedate=September 16, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> Previously, Barnes & Noble operated the chain of small [[B. Dalton|B. Dalton Bookseller]] stores in malls until they announced the liquidation of the chain. The company was also one of the nation's largest manager of college textbook stores located on or near many college campuses when that division was spun off as a separate public company called [[#Barnes & Noble Education|Barnes & Noble Education]] in 2015.\n\nThe company is known by its customers for large retail outlets, many of which contain a [[caf\u00e9]] serving [[Starbucks]] [[coffee]] and other consumables. Most stores sell books, magazines, newspapers, DVDs, graphic novels, gifts, games, toys, music, and [[Barnes & Noble Nook|Nook]]&nbsp;[[e-reader|e&#8209;reader]]s and [[tablet computer|tablets]].\n\n==History==\n===19th century: Foundations===\n[[File:Clifford Noble in 1893.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Clifford Noble in 1893]]\nBarnes & Noble began in 1886 as a bookstore called '''Arthur Hinds & Company''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/shephyken/2018/04/08/arming-the-davids-of-industry-against-disruptive-goliaths/#6fd75b466c84 |last=Hyken |first=Shep |date=April 8, 2018 |title=Barnes & Noble, Amazon, Independents: Who's Disrupting Whom? |work=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref> located in the Cooper Union Building in [[New York City]].<ref>\"Barnes & Noble to Move.\" The Bookseller and Stationer, January 1. 1922 p. 13</ref><ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|0595374786}}, 9780595374786 page 71</ref> In the fall of 1886, Gilbert Clifford Noble, a then-recent [[Harvard University|Harvard]] graduate from [[Westfield, Massachusetts]], was hired to work there as a clerk.<ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|0595374786}}, 9780595374786 page 65</ref> \n\nIn 1894, Noble was made a partner, and the name of the shop was changed to Hinds & Noble.<ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|0595374786}}, 9780595374786 page 101</ref> \n\n===20th century: Expansion===\n====1900\u20131919====\nIn 1901, Hinds & Noble moved to 31\u201335 W. 15th Street.<ref>\"Barnes & Noble to Move.\" ''The Bookseller and Stationer'', January 1. 1922 p. 13</ref>\n\nIn 1917, Noble bought out Hinds and entered into a partnership with William Barnes, son of his old friend Charles Barnes; the name of the store was changed to Barnes & Noble soon after.<ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|0595374786}}, 9780595374786 page 151</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Cynthia |last=Blair |title=1917: First Barnes & Noble Bookstore Opens in Manhattan |url=http://www.newsday.com/about/ny-ihiny021705story,0,5026610.htmlstory |newspaper=[[Newsday]] |accessdate=2007-08-01 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001000727/http://www.newsday.com/about/ny-ihiny021705story%2C0%2C5026610.htmlstory |archivedate=October 1, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> Charles had previously opened a book-printing business in [[Wheaton, Illinois]] in 1873, named the C. M. Barnes-Wilcox Company; William Barnes, however, divested himself of his ownership interest in his father's business shortly before his partnership with Noble. (His father's company would go on to become the [[Follett Corporation]].) Although the flagship store once featured the motto \"Founded in 1873,\" the C. M. Barnes-Wilcox Company never had any connection with Barnes & Noble, save for the fact that both were partly owned (at different times) by William Barnes.\n\n====1920\u20131939====\n[[File:Barnes & Noble Fifth Ave flagship.jpg|thumb|right|Barnes & Noble's former flagship store at 105 [[Fifth Avenue]] in [[Manhattan]], New York, that operated from 1932 to 2014.]]\n\nIn 1930, Noble sold his share of the company to William Barnes' son, John Wilcox Barnes.<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 62\">''The Late Age of Print: Everyday Book Culture from Consumerism to Control'' by Theodore G. Striphas. Columbia University Press: 2009. 978-0-231-14814-6 p. 62</ref> Noble died on June 6, 1936, at the age of 72.<ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|9780595374786}} page 153</ref> In 1932, at the height of the [[Great Depression]], the bookstore moved its flagship location to 18th Street and [[Fifth Avenue]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tmHEm5ohoCUC&pg=PA1266&dq=%22flagship+store%22+1932+barnes+noble&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WNETUuC3NMjnqAGThoGoBw&ved=0CFAQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22flagship%20store%22%201932%20barnes%20noble&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of New York State|editor=Eisenstadt, Peter|work=Syracuse University Press|page=1266|year=2004}}</ref> which served as the company's flagship location until its closure in 2014. The Noble family retained ownership of an associated publishing business, and Barnes & Noble opened a new publishing division in 1931.<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 62\"/>\n\n====1940\u20131959====\nIn 1940, the store was one of the first businesses to feature [[Muzak Holdings|Muzak]] and it underwent a major renovation the following year.<ref>''The Late Age of Print: Everyday Book Culture from Consumerism to Control'' by Theodore G. Striphas. Columbia University Press: 2009. 978-0-231-14814-6 p. 64</ref> That decade the company opened stores in Brooklyn and Chicago.<ref name=\"Barnes pg 78\">''Barnes & Noble: Groundbreaking Entrepreneurs'' by Kayla Morgan. Abdo Publishing: 2000 {{ISBN|9781604537581}} p. 78</ref> William Barnes died in 1945, at the age of 78, and his son John Wilcox Barnes assumed full control.<ref name=\"Barnes pg 78\"/>  The company underwent a significant expansion between the 1950s and the 1960s, opening an additional retail store on 23rd Street in Manhattan, as well as shops near the City University of New York, Harvard, and other Northeast college campuses.<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 65\">''The Late Age of Print: Everyday Book Culture from Consumerism to Control'' by Theodore G. Striphas. Columbia University Press: 2009. 978-0-231-14814-6 p. 65</ref>\n\n====1960\u20131979====\n[[File:122 Fifth Avenue.jpg|left|thumb|167px|Barnes & Noble corporate headquarters, 122 (122\u2013124) Fifth Avenue between West 17th and 18th Streets in the Flatiron District neighborhood of Manhattan, New York City]]\n[[File:Barnes & Noble sign.jpg|thumb|right|200px|5th Avenue store sign]]\nJohn Barnes died in 1964, and the company was sold to the conglomerate Amtel two years later.<ref>''Reluctant Capitalists: Bookselling and the Culture of Consumption'' by Laura J. Miller.  University Of Chicago Press: 2007 p. 47</ref> The business was then purchased in 1971 by [[Leonard Riggio]], who has been credited as one of the founders,<ref name=\"water_stones\"/><ref name=\"imprint\"/> for $1.2 million.<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 65\"/> By then, it had been mismanaged and consisted only of \"a significantly reduced wholesale operation and a single retail location\u2014the flagship store at 105 Fifth Avenue.\"<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 65\"/> The publishing operation was sold separately by Amtel to [[Harper & Row]].<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Gale Research Company| isbn = 0-8103-1724-9| volume = 46| pages = [https://archive.org/details/americanliterary0046unse/page/40 40]| editor = Peter Dzwonkoski| last = Wilkinson| first = Carol| title = American literary publishing houses, 1900-1980. edited by Peter Dzwonkoski.| chapter = Barnes & Noble Books| location = Detroit, Mich.| series = Dictionary of literary biography| date = 1986| url = https://archive.org/details/americanliterary0046unse/page/40}}</ref> In 1974, Barnes & Noble became the first bookstore chain to advertise on television and a year later, the company became the first bookseller in the United States to discount books, by selling ''[[The New York Times]]'' best-selling titles at 40% off the publishers' list price.<ref name=hist>{{Cite journal|title=Barnes & Noble History |url=http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/history/bn_history.html#H3 |accessdate=2008-06-13 |publisher=Barnes &amp; Noble |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509130810/http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/history/bn_history.html |archivedate=May 9, 2008 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> Between the 1970s and the 1980s, Barnes & Noble opened smaller discount stores, which were eventually phased out in favor of larger stores. They also began to publish their own books to be sold to mail-order customers. These titles were primarily affordable reissues of out-of-print titles and selling them through mail-order catalogs allowed Barnes & Noble to reach new customers nationwide.<ref name=hist />\n\nIn November 1974, editors of the British-produced ''[[Guinness Book of Records]]'', claimed on the [[BBC One]] television programme [[Record Breakers]] that the Fifth Avenue store of Barnes & Noble had overtaken that of London's [[Foyles]] bookshop to become the world's biggest bookstore.<ref>''Record Breakers''. Presented by Roy Castle. Co-presented by Norris and Ross McWhirter. BBC 1. Broadcast on Tuesday November 19, 1974.</ref>\n\n====1980\u20131999====\nBarnes & Noble continued to expand throughout the 1980s, and it purchased the primarily [[shopping mall]]-based [[B. Dalton]] chain from [[Dayton Hudson]] in 1986, for an estimated $275 million to $300 million.<ref name=bloomberg>{{cite news|first=Stephen|last=Miller |title=Bruce Dayton, CEO of Retailer That Became Target, Dies at 97 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-11-13/bruce-dayton-who-led-family-s-dayton-hudson-stores-dies-at-97 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=2015-10-13 |accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref> Solveig Robinson, author of ''The Book in Society: An Introduction to Print Culture'', wrote that the purchase \"gave [Barnes & Noble] the necessary know-how and infrastructure to create what, in 1992, became the definitive bookselling superstore.\"<ref>Robinson, Solveig. ''The Book in Society: An Introduction to Print Culture''. [[Broadview Press]], November 15, 2013. {{ISBN|1770484310}}, 9781770484313. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=qfKuAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA260 260].</ref> The acquisition of the 797 B. Dalton bookstores turned the company into a nationwide retailer, and by the end of fiscal year 1999, the second-largest online bookseller in the United States.<ref name=\"BIannual1999\">{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/for_investors/annual_reports/bnannual99.pdf|title=BarnesAndNobleInc.com|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-09-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116003831/http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/for_investors/annual_reports/bnannual99.pdf|archive-date=January 16, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> B&N's critics claim that it has contributed to the decline of local and independent booksellers.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Warren |last=St. John |title=Barnes & Noble's Epiphany |url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/7.06/barnes.html |date=July 6, 1999 |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=2008-05-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506092855/http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/7.06/barnes.html |archivedate=May 6, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> The last B. Dalton stores were scheduled to close in January 2010.<ref name=\"BIannual1999\" />  \n\nIn 1989, Barnes & Noble purchased the 22-store chain [[Bookstop (company)|Bookstop]].\n\nIn September 1993, Barnes & Noble became a publicly traded company by issuing $77 million worth of stock on the New York Stock Exchange under the BKS ticker symbol.<ref name=\"nyt-1993sep03\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/03/business/barnes-noble-goes-public-vol-2.html?pagewanted=all |title=Barnes & Noble Goes Public: Vol. 2 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 3, 1993 |first=Stephanie |last=Strom |page=D1}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-1993sep28\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/28/business/company-news-barnes-noble-offering-price-rises-to-20-a-share.html?pagewanted=all |title=Barnes & Noble Offering Price Rises to $20 A Share |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 28, 1993 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |page=D4}}</ref> The company remained on the stock exchange until August 2019 when Elliot Management purchased all of the company's stock and took the company private.\n\nBefore Barnes & Noble created its official website, it sold books directly to customers through mail-order catalogs. It first began selling books online through an early [[videotex]] service called \"[[Prodigy (online service)|Trintex]],\" a joint venture between [[Sears]] and [[IBM]], but the company's website was not launched until May 1997.<ref name=BNSiteHistory /> BarnesandNoble.com went public in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/1999/05/24/technology/barnesandnoble/|title=Barnesandnoble sets IPO at $18  - May 24, 1999|website=money.cnn.com|access-date=2018-08-22}}</ref>\n\n===21st century: Operating in an electronic environment===\n====2000s====\nIn 2004, it was reported that the reading of books was on the decline in America, with the number of non-reading adults increasing by 17 million between 1992 and 2002. Despite this, Barnes & Noble claimed that its retail store business was expanding in the book market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/huge-decline-in-book-reading/|title=Huge Decline In Book Reading|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref> Beginning in 1999, Barnes & Noble owned [[GameStop]], a video game and electronics retail outlet. The company distributed its shares in GameStop in late 2004, spinning it off into its own company in an attempt to simplify its corporate structure.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnes & Noble Pares GameStop |author=Jeffrey A. Trachtenberg|date=October 5, 2004 |work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\nCEO Leonard Riggio stepped down in 2002, naming his younger brother and former acting chief executive of BarnesandNoble.com, Stephen Riggio, to succeed him. Some corporate governance experts noted that this appointment could potentially cause conflict of interest, but the company board noted that Riggio's experience at the company made him the right person for the job.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/14/business/shifting-leadership-bookseller-barnes-noble-chief-steps-aside-for-brother.html|title=A Shifting Of Leadership At Bookseller; Barnes & Noble Chief Steps Aside for Brother|last=Kirkpatrick|first=David D.|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref> Stephen Riggio stepped down from the position in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/03/18/barnes-nobles-ceo-steps-down-bn-com-president-william-lynch-takes-over/|title=Barnes & Noble CEO Steps Down, BN.com President William Lynch Takes Over|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n====2010s====\nIn 2010, website president William Lynch was named CEO. He is credited with helping launch the company's [[electronic book]] store and overseeing the introduction of its [[e-reader|electronic book reader]], the [[Nook]]. Many observers saw his appointment as underscoring the importance of digital books to Barnes & Noble's future. Steve Riggio stayed on as vice chairman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/companies/management/2010-03-18-barnes-and-noble-execs_N.htm |title=Barnes & Noble names website head William Lynch as CEO|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date= March 18, 2010}}</ref>  When Lynch resigned in mid-2013,<ref>{{cite web|author=Brown, Abram|title=Barnes & Noble CEO Lynch Out After Nook Woes Deepen|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/abrambrown/2013/07/08/barnes-noble-ceo-lynch-out-after-kindle-woes-deepen/|work=Forbes|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> he was replaced by Chief Financial Officer Michael Huseby early the next year.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.marketwatch.com/story/barnes-noble-appoints-michael-p-huseby-chief-executive-officer-2014-01-08|publisher=Market Watch|title=Barnes & Noble points Michael P. Huseby CEO|date=January 8, 2014 }}</ref> Following the spinoff of Barnes & Noble Education, Huseby departed to head the new firm; his place was filled in mid-2015 by Ronald Boire,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/business/media/barnes-noble-names-ronald-boire-of-sears-canada-ceo.html|title=Barnes &amp; Noble Names Ronald Boire of Sears Canada as C.E.O.|date=July 3, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Barnes & Noble Completes Spin-Off of Barnes & Noble Education|url=http://next.bncollege.com/barnes-noble-completes-spin-off-of-barnes-noble-education/}}</ref> who departed one year later.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barnes & Noble Says CEO Boire 'Not a Good Fit' and Will Step Down|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/barnes-noble-ceo-ronald-boire-is-leaving-1471380961|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Demos Parneros was named Barnes & Noble's Chief Executive Officer in April 2017 after having joined the company as Chief Operating Officer in November 2016; however, he was fired in July 2018 for \"company policy violations\" without severance and was immediately removed from the company's board, at the advice of a law firm hired by Barnes & Noble.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/07/03/news/companies/barnes-noble-fires-ceo/index.html|title=Barnes & Noble fires CEO for violating company policy|last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=2018-07-03|work=[[CNNMoney]]|access-date=2018-07-04}}</ref> On August 28, 2018, Parneros filed a lawsuit against Barnes & Noble, claiming wrongful termination.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/work/1372756/fired-barnes-noble-ceo-demos-parneros-sues-for-wrongful-termination/|title=A lawsuit by a fired Barnes & Noble CEO is a spectacular example of not going quietly|work=Quartz at Work|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nAfter the bankruptcy and closure of its chief competitor, [[Borders Group]], in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|last=Leopold|first=Todd|title=The death and life of a great American bookstore|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/09/12/first.borders.bookstore.closing/|work=CNN|accessdate=October 30, 2013|date=September 12, 2011}}</ref> Barnes & Noble became the last remaining national bookstore chain in the United States.<ref name=\"wp\"/><ref name=\"bw\"/> This followed a series of mergers and bankruptcies in the American bookstore industry since the 1990s, which also saw the demise of [[Waldenbooks]], Barnes & Noble's own subsidiary [[B. Dalton]], and [[Crown Books]], among others. Barnes & Noble's largest physical bookstore rival is now [[Books-A-Million]], which does not operate in the Western US. Barnes & Noble also faces competition from general retailers, especially from [[Amazon.com]], and from regional and independent booksellers. Amazon has even opened its own physical bookstores, once again creating a second national bookstore chain.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/bea/article/73837-bookexpo-2017-amazon-will-be-the-fifth-largest-bookstore-chain.html|title=Amazon Will Be the Fifth Largest Bookstore Chain|magazine=Publisher's Weekly|date=June 1, 2017|accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBarnes & Noble began reducing its overall presence in the 2010s, closing its original flagship store in early 2014.<ref name=\"crains\">{{cite news |first=Adrianne |last=Pasquarelli |authorlink= |title=Barnes & Noble closes the book on Fifth Ave. store |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20140107/RETAIL_APPAREL/140109914 |work=[[Crain Communications|Crain's New York Business]] |date=January 7, 2014 | page= |accessdate=2015-09-01}}</ref> In mid-2014, the company announced it would separate its Nook Media division from its retail store division.<ref name=\"Franzen, Carl\">{{cite web|author=Franzen, Carl|title=Barnes & Noble is splitting into two companies: one for Nooks and one for books|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/6/25/5841278/barnes-noble-is-splitting-into-two-companies-nook-and-books}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Barnes & Noble permanently laid off 1,800 full time employees at an annual cost savings of $40 million per year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/13/barnes-noble-confirms-job-cuts-expects-40-million-in-cost-savings.html|title=Barnes & Noble confirms job cuts, expects $40 million in annual cost savings|last=Thomas|first=Lauren|date=2018-02-13|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-08-22}}</ref> According to ''[[TechCrunch]]'', the company essentially fired their entire full time staff at all their stores, who would be making an average of $22,000 per year (~$11 per hour), and were replaced by part time workers earning close to minimum wage.<ref name=\"techcrunch-2018feb16\">{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/02/16/barnes-noble-is-killing-itself/ |title=Barnes & Noble is killing itself |website=[[TechCrunch]] |date=February 16, 2018 |first=John |last=Biggs}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 fiscal year that ended in July, the company overall losses reached $17 million.<ref name=\"forbes-2018sep06\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andriacheng/2018/09/06/barnes-nobles-problem-is-no-longer-about-amazon/#9d2398244d08 |title=Barnes & Noble's Problem Is No Longer Just Amazon |magazine=[[Forbes]] |date=September 6, 2018 |first=Andria |last=Cheng}}</ref> \n\nIn early July 2018, Barnes & Noble fired CEO Demos Parneros for an unspecified violation of company policy, which was later revealed to be over sexual harassment claims.<ref>{{cite news|author=Meyersohn, Nathaniel|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/09/06/news/companies/barnes-and-noble-books-amazon/index.html|title=Barnes & Noble is overrun with problems|date=2018-09-06|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=2019-11-15|language=en-US}}</ref> It accused Pareneros of breaching his duties of loyalty and good faith and acting as a \"[[faithless servant]]\" by sexually harassing the female employee, bullying subordinates, and attempting to \"sabotage\" a potential acquisition of the New York-based company, and asserted that the company should therefore be entitled to [[claw back]] his salary, bonus, and other benefits during the period of his \"disloyal conduct\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/barnes-noble-lawsuit/corrected-barnes-noble-countersues-ex-ceo-it-fired-after-alleged-harassment-idUSL2N1XA25U|last=Stempel |first=Jonathan |date=October 30, 2018|title=-Barnes & Noble countersues ex-CEO it fired after alleged harassment|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 2018, the board of directors announced that they would entertain offers to buy the company. Among the potential buyers was Leonard Riggio, who owns approximately 19% of Barnes & Noble stock. As a result of the news, the company's stock price jumped by nearly 30%.<ref name=\"fm-2018oct03\">{{cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2018/10/03/barnes-noble-sale/ |title=Barnes & Noble Considers Selling Itself Yet Again |magazine=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune Magazine]] |date=October 3, 2018 |first=Phil |last=Wahba}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, [[Elliott Management Corporation]] acquired the company<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190807005399/en/Elliott-Completes-Acquisition-Barnes-Noble | title=Elliott Completes Acquisition of Barnes & Noble | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=August 7, 2019}}</ref> for approximately $683m with [[James Daunt]], the [[managing director]] of [[London]]-based [[Waterstones|Waterstones Booksellers Ltd.]], becoming CEO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/elliott-buy-barnes-noble-daunt-will-run-both-chains-1020446|last=Jones |first=Philip |date=June 7, 2019|title=Elliott to buy Barnes & Noble; Daunt will run both chains|work=[[The Bookseller website]]}}</ref>\n\n==Publishing==<!-- This section is linked from [[Nine Men's Morris]] -->\nBarnes & Noble maintains a separate publishing business in addition to its retail stores and other entities. Barnes & Noble's publishing company got its start by reissuing inexpensive versions of out-of-print books, and made a push to expand the unit in 2003. The company saw success the following year; in September 2004, its book, \"Hippie,\" reached [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/09/books/huge-book-retailer-expands-its-publishing-role.html?mtrref=www.google.com|title=Huge Book Retailer Expands Its Publishing Role|last=Wyatt|first=Edward|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref> \n\nBarnes & Noble often publishes and sells books at a lower cost than competitors, and sells lines of inexpensive books like Barnes & Noble Classics.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition, the company has a second paperback series called the ''Barnes & Noble Library of Essential Reading''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/u/Barnes-and-Noble-Library-of-Essential-Readings/379001270/|title=Barnes & Noble Library of Essential Reading|publisher=Barnes & Noble|accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref>Barnes & Noble's edition of ''The Gentle Art of Verbal Self-Defense'' by [[Suzette Haden Elgin]], has sold over 250,000 copies,<ref name=BNSiteHistory /> and its reissued edition of ''The Columbia History of the World'' by John Garrity, has sold over 1 million copies.<ref name=BNSiteHistory>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/history/bn_history.html |title=Barnes & Noble History|website= Barnes & Noble Inc.|accessdate= September 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/8527098/Barnes-and-Noble-a-history.html|title=Barnes & Noble: a history|date=2011-05-20|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThe company has expanded business by acquiring several firms over the years, including J.B. Fairfax International in 1999<ref>{{Cite web| title = B&N Buys J.B. Fairfax International| work = PublishersWeekly.com| accessdate = 2020-03-28| url = https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/19990816/39525-b-amp-n-buys-j-b-fairfax-international.html}}</ref>, [[SparkNotes]], an educational website and publishing company, in 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sec.edgar-online.com/2001/06/18/0000950123-01-503532/Section2.asp |title=Barnes & Noble inc - BKS Quarterly Report (10-Q) Item 1: Financial Statements |accessdate=2008-02-05 |date=18 June 2001 |publisher=Edgar Online |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224133049/http://sec.edgar-online.com/2001/06/18/0000950123-01-503532/Section2.asp |archivedate=December 24, 2007 }}</ref> and [[Sterling Publishing]] in 2003.<ref name=BNSiteHistory/>\n\n==Food service==\n[[File:6.25.11SpringfieldBarnes&NobleByLuigiNovi.jpg|thumb|left|The Barnes & Noble caf\u00e9 in [[Springfield Township, Union County, New Jersey|Springfield, New Jersey]]]]\nIn 1993, Barnes & Noble signed an agreement to serve Starbucks coffee in each of its existing and future cafes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930907&slug=1719818|title=Business {{!}} Starbucks Co. Books Space In Barnes & Noble Chain {{!}} Seattle Times Newspaper|website=community.seattletimes.nwsource.com|access-date=2018-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.strategy-business.com/article/20534?gko=582b3|title=The Barista Principle \u2014 Starbucks and the Rise of Relational Capital|last=Neilson|first=Ranjay Gulati, Sarah Huffman, and Gary L.|work=strategy+business|access-date=2017-08-09}}</ref> In 2004, Barnes & Noble began offering [[Wi-Fi]] in the caf\u00e9 area of selected stores, using SBC FreedomLink (now the [[AT&T Inc.|AT&T]] Wi-Fi network). All stores offered Wi-Fi as of 2006 and as of July 27, 2009, Wi-Fi is offered for free to all customers. <ref>Colker, David. [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/technology/2009/07/free-wifi-barnes-nobel-starbucks-att.html \"Internet wants to be free at Barnes & Noble\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', July 29, 2009</ref>[[File:Barnes & Noble Interior.JPG|thumb|right|The Barnes & Noble at [[The Grove at Farmers Market]], [[Los Angeles]].]]\n[[Image:Bnlynnwood.jpg|thumb|right|Barnes & Noble in [[Lynnwood, Washington]], using the former 1990s era logo.]]\n\nIn 2016, Barnes & Noble announced plans to open four concept stores in 2017 that featured caf\u00e9s twice the size of its usual food spots, as well as bars offering wine and beer. Restaurants would also include a waitstaff and a full menu for breakfast, lunch, and dinner. The restaurants were expected to revive sales growth. Company executives planned to open additional concept stores if sales met expectations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2016/06/23/barnes-and-noble-wine/|title=Cheers? Barnes & Noble Is Getting Into the Bars and Restaurant Business|work=Fortune|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref> The first stores were opened in [[Scarsdale, New York]], [[Edina, Minnesota]], [[Plano, Texas]], and [[Folsom, California]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nrn.com/casual-dining/barnes-noble-continues-expand-full-service-kitchen|title=Barnes & Noble continues to expand full-service Kitchen|date=2017-11-10|work=Nation's Restaurant News|access-date=2018-03-16}}</ref> Easter Egg.\n\n==Community involvement==\nBarnes & Noble hires community business development managers to engage in community outreach.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsminer.com/readers_choice/barnes-noble-voted-best-local-bookstore/article_c43a032c-920a-11e8-97f6-fff74df2cd9d.html|title=Barnes & Noble voted best local bookstore|last=intern|first=David Jones, News-Miner|work=Fairbanks Daily News-Miner|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/chattanooganow/outabout/story/2018/aug/08/pick-page-turner-book-sellers-name-their-summ/476528/|title=Pick up a page-turner: Book-sellers name their summer reading picks|last=|first=|date=8 August 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Barnes & Noble also gives back to the community to increase literacy and education. The Barnes & Noble located in Fairbanks, Alaska gave over $80,000 to the community between 2015 and 2018 through book fair fundraising programs.<ref name=\":1\" /> To promote nationwide literacy among 1st through 6th graders and encourage more reading during the summer, Barnes & Noble has implemented a summer challenge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/summerreading/|title=Summer Reading Challenge|work=Barnes & Noble website |accessdate=2009-05-08| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430094614/http://www.barnesandnoble.com/summerreading/| archivedate=April 30, 2009 | url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fool.com/earnings/call-transcripts/2018/06/22/barnes-noble-bks-q4-2018-earnings-conference-call.aspx|title=Barnes & Noble (BKS) Q4 2018 Earnings Conference Call Transcript|last=Staff|first=Motley Fool|work=The Motley Fool|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/ads/other/ads/fun-stuff-for-kids-online/ad_c0b49d72-9672-11e8-9b90-9b4fe3103637.html|title=Fun Stuff for Kids Online|website=Sioux City Journal|language=en|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref>\n\n== ''The Barnes & Noble Review'' ==\n'''''The Barnes & Noble Review''''' is an [[online magazine]], hosted on Barnes & Noble's website, that publishes evaluations of both fiction and nonfiction works, along with essays, interviews, and pieces on other topics. It was launched in October 2007 by Barnes & Noble CEO Steve Riggio and [[James Mustich, Jr.]], publisher of the book catalog [[A Common Reader]]. Regular contributors to the magazine have included book critics [[Michael Dirda]], Brooke Allen, Laura Miller, and [[Adam Kirsch]], as well as prominent writers in fields outside of literary criticism, such as political journalists [[Chris Hayes]] and [[Ezra Klein]], philosopher [[A.\u2009C. Grayling]], music critic [[Robert Christgau]], and cartoonist [[Ward Sutton]]. Miller, who has written for ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' and Mustich's Common Reader, said, \"The reviews [at ''BNR''] are the same as anywhere else\", adding that the tone and length of the pieces evoke ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' rather than the less formal ''Salon''. The magazine's [[web traffic]] flourished during its first few years. According to [[Compete.com]], it amassed 50,000 [[unique user|unique visitors]] in December 2009.<ref name=\"CJR\">{{cite magazine|last=Smith|first=Jordan Michael|date=April 2010|url=https://archives.cjr.org/review/critical_condition.php|title=Critical Condition|magazine=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome critics were originally skeptical of ''The Barnes & Noble Review''. Art Winslow, former literary editor of ''[[The Nation]]'', said that because Barnes & Noble is a [[brand name]], ''BNR''{{'}}s contributors are effectively endorsing the corporation, and that the motives behind the publication undermine its integrity: \"Criticism's content should be free of any commercialism. Barnes & Noble has found another way to sell books, and that's the ''Review''. ... I wouldn't write there.\" Mustich disputed the idea that the magazine serves as a corporate tactic: \"We counter that skepticism with quality. If people read the site, they can determine that we are doing what we purport to do. They have never tried to influence my judgment. The first attempt would have been the last.\"<ref name=\"CJR\"/>\n\n==Barnes & Noble Nook==\n{{See also|Barnes & Noble Nook}}\nBarnes & Noble Nook (styled NOOK) is a suite of [[e-book]] readers developed by the company,<ref>{{cite news|author=Jeffrey A. Trachtenberg and Geoffrey A. Fowler|title=B&N Reader Out Tuesday|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703816204574483790552304348|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=October 20, 2009|accessdate=October 20, 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091021225827/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703816204574483790552304348.html|archivedate=October 21, 2009|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> based on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] platform. The first device was announced in the [[United States]] on October 20, 2009 and was released November 30, 2009, for $259.<ref>{{cite web |author=Ina Fried|title=Barnes & Noble's 'Nook' said to cost $259|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13860_3-10378525-56.html|work=|publisher=[[CNET Networks|cnet news]]|date=October 19, 2009|accessdate=October 20, 2009}}</ref> On June 21, 2010, Barnes & Noble reduced the Nook's price to $199, as well as launched a new [[Wi-Fi]]-only model, for $149, and released a Nook colored touch screen for $249.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/06/21/tech/main6603068.shtml|work=[[CBS News]]| title=Barnes & Noble Cuts Nook Price|date=June 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Nook competes with the [[Amazon Kindle]], [[Kobo eReader]], and other e-reader offerings and color tablets with reading apps, such as Apple's [[iBooks]] for [[iOS]] devices. Various Nook models feature a 6-inch, 7-inch, or larger [[touchscreen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/nook/features/index.asp |website=Barnes & Noble|title=Nook Features}}</ref> Version 1.3 of the Nook introduced [[Wi-Fi]] connectivity, a web browser, a dictionary, [[chess]], and [[sudoku]] games, and a separate, smaller color touchscreen that serves as the primary input device. The Nook also features a Read in Store capability that allows visitors to stream and read any book for up to one hour while shopping in a Barnes & Noble bookstore. According to a June 2010 [[CNet]] article, the company planned to expand this feature to include periodicals in the near future.<ref>{{cite web |author=David Carnoy|title=B&N delivers meaty Nook update, teases iPad app|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17938_105-20003085-1.html|work=|publisher=[[CNET Networks|cnet news]]|date=April 23, 2010 |accessdate=June 7, 2010}}</ref> The [[Nook Color|color version of the Nook]] introduced a 7-inch color touchscreen and the ability to view at a portrait or landscape orientation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/nookcolor/features/index.asp |title=Nook Color Features|website= Barnes &. Noble|accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 2012, Microsoft invested $300 million for a 17.6% stake in Nook, which valued the business at about $1.7 billion.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ovide |first=Shira |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303916904577375502392129654 |title=Microsoft to Invest in Barnes & Noble's Nook |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=May 2, 2012 |accessdate=2012-09-18|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, the technology publications ''[[Mashable]]'' and ''[[Techdirt]]'' criticized the license agreement with which Barnes & Noble sells ebooks to consumers, pointing out that the rights to re-download a purchased ebook [[digital rights management|expire when the customer's credit card expires]], and a valid credit card must be added to the account to restore this functionality.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rosen, Kenneth |date=November 28, 2012|url=http://mashable.com/2012/11/28/barnes-and-noble-ereader/ |title=Barnes &amp; Noble: That Ebook is Only Yours Until Your Credit Card Expires|work= [[Mashable]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Cushing, Tim |date=November 27, 2012|url=http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20121126/18084721154/barnes-noble-decides-that-purchased-ebooks-are-only-yours-until-your-credit-card-expires.shtml |title=Barnes & Noble Decides That Purchased Ebooks Are Only Yours Until Your Credit Card Expires|work= [[Techdirt]]}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Barnes & Noble had previously announced that it would spin off its Nook Digital division into a separate publicly traded company,<ref name=\"Franzen, Carl\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-digital-reader.com/2015/02/26/bn-to-split-off-college-stores-retain-nook-and-retail-stores/|title= B&N to Split Off College Stores, Retain Nook and Retail Stores|work=The Digital Reader|accessdate= July 6, 2015|date=February 26, 2015}}</ref> but as of 2016, Nook remains a part of Barnes & Noble. That same month, the company announced a partnership with [[Samsung Electronics]] to make Nook tablets, as the bookseller moved forward with plans to revamp its digital business.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barnes & Noble Partners With Samsung to Make Nook Tablets|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/industries/2014/06/05/barnes-noble-to-develop-tablets-with-samsung/|work=FOXBusiness|date=June 5, 2014|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> Samsung and Barnes & Noble introduced the [[Samsung Galaxy Tab 4 Nook 7.0]] in August 2014, followed by the [[Samsung Galaxy Tab 4 Nook 10.1]] in October 2014. In December 2014, Barnes & Noble announced that it had ended its Nook partnership with Microsoft by buying back its stake.<ref>{{cite web|title=Microsoft, Barnes & Noble bring their weird Nook \"partnership\" to a formal end|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/12/microsoft-barnes-noble-bring-their-weird-nook-partnership-to-a-formal-end/|work=Ars Technica|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=December 26, 2014}}</ref> Samsung and Barnes & Noble continue to introduce new Nook tablets.<ref>{{cite news|work=PC Magazine|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2490627,00.asp|date=September 2015|title=Samsung and Barnes & Noble introduced the  Samsung Galaxy Tab S2 NOOK}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Barnes & Noble announced it would close the Nook App Store and Nook Video and in the UK close the Nook Store on March 15.<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/4/11160942/barnes-noble-nook-app-store-shutting-down-march-15th Barnes & Noble is shutting down the Nook App Store on March 15th] Retrieved March 4, 2016.</ref> It will continue to sell e-books as well as digital magazines and newspapers in the US.\n\n=={{anchor|Barnes & Noble Education}}College bookstores==\n{{See also|Barnes & Noble College Booksellers}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Barnes & Noble Education, Inc.\n| logo             = <!-- PLEASE ADD LOGO HERE -->\n| logo_size        = \n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = {{nyse|BNED}}\n| predecessor      = [[Corporate spin-off]] from Barnes & Noble, Inc.\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|2015|08|03}}\n| location_city    = [[Basking Ridge, New Jersey]]\n| location_country = United States\n| locations        = 773 (December 2018)<ref name=\"bw-2018dec04\" />\n| key_people       = Michael P. Huseby (CEO, chairman)\n| products         = \n| brands           = Yuzu digital textbook platform\n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| num_employees    = \n| divisions        = {{ublist|[[Barnes & Noble College Booksellers]]|MBS Textbook Exchange|Digital Student Solutions}}\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.bned.com/}}\n}}\n\nIn February 2015, Barnes & Noble had announced plans to spin off its college bookstore assets and create a separate company called Barnes & Noble Education.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2015/02/26/barnes-noble-college-spinoff/|title=Barnes & Noble is spinning off its college store business |magazine=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |access-date=2018-08-30 |first=John |last=Kell |date=February 26, 2015}}</ref> On August 3, 2015, Barnes & Noble Education, Inc. began trading on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] under the [[ticker symbol]], \"BNED\".<ref name=\"thestreet.com-2015aug03\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestreet.com/story/13241726/1/barnes-and-noble-education-spins-off-looks-for-growth-in-digital-textbooks-colleges.html |title=Barnes and Noble Education Spins Off, Looks for Growth in Digital Textbooks, Colleges: Barnes and Noble Education rang the opening bell at the New York Stock Exchange after spinning off from Barnes and Noble, and will have its own board and management team. |website=[[TheStreet.com]] |date=August 3, 2015 |first=Rhonda |last=Schaffler}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/08/30/barnes-noble-education-shares-plunge-earnings-miss/615691001/ |title=Barnes & Noble Education shares plunge on earnings miss |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |access-date=2018-08-30 |first=Kevin |last=McCoy |date=August 30, 2017}}</ref> The company operated stores dedicated to selling college textbooks, both on and off campus.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[Crain's New York]] |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20140107/RETAIL_APPAREL/140109914/barnes-noble-closes-the-book-on-fifth-ave-store |title=Barnes & Noble closes the book on Fifth Avenue Store |date=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Barnes & Noble Education had acquired MBS Textbook Exchange, a major textbook distributor based in [[Columbia, Missouri]], for $174.2 million in cash.<ref name=\"kbia-2017mar01\">{{cite news |url=http://www.kbia.org/post/barnes-and-noble-education-buys-mbs-textbook-exchange |title=Barnes and Noble Education Buys MBS Textbook Exchange |website=[[KBIA]] |date=March 1, 2017 |first=Beatriz Costa |last=Lima}}</ref><ref name=\"bw-2017feb28\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20170228005977/en/Barnes-Noble-Education-Acquires-MBS-174.2-Million |title=Barnes & Noble Education Acquires MBS for $174.2 Million |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=February 28, 2017 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2018, Barnes & Noble Education had operated or managed 773 campus bookstores under contracts.<ref name=\"bw-2018dec04\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20181204005215/en/Barnes-Noble-Education-Reports-Quarter-Fiscal-Year |title=Barnes & Noble Education Reports Second Quarter Fiscal Year 2019 Financial Results |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=December 4, 2018 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Barnes & Noble Education revealed that the company had turned down several offers by California-based Bay Capital Finance to take over the company citing that the offers by Bay Capital were \"substantially undervalued BNED, were highly conditional and not credible.\"<ref name=\"forbes-2019jul28\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ellenduffer/2019/07/28/barnes--noble-education-declines-acquisition-offer/ |title=Barnes & Noble Education Declines Acquisition Offer |magazine=[[Forbes]] |date=July 28, 2019 |first=Ellen |last=Duffer}}</ref> Unlike its former parent company, BNED was diversifying its business by the acquisition of many digital services companies to increase the number of services offered by its Digital Student Solutions division during its past four years as an independent company.\n\n===Digital Student Solutions division===\nIn March 2016, Barnes & Noble Education enlarged their Digital Student Solutions online services division by acquiring LoudCloud Systems, a digital platform and analytics provider to clients in higher education, the for-profit sector, and K-12 segment.<ref name=\"bw-2016mar08\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20160308005868/en/Barnes-Noble-Education-Announces-Acquisition-LoudCloud-Systems |title=Barnes & Noble Education, Inc. Announces the Acquisition of LoudCloud Systems |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=March 8, 2016 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Barnes & Noble Education acquired Student Brands for $58.5 Million.<ref name=\"pw-2017aug07\">{{cite news |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/industry-deals/article/74428-b-n-education-buys-student-brands-for-58-5-million.html |title=B&N Education Buys Student Brands for $58.5 Million |newspaper=[[Publishers Weekly]] |date=August 7, 2017 |first=Jim |last=Milliot}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Barnes & Noble Education acquired PaperRater, a service that help students write papers and identify plagiarism.<ref name=\"marketwatch-2018aug22\">{{cite news |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/press-release/barnes-noble-education-acquires-paperratercom-2018-08-22 |title=Barnes & Noble Education Acquires PaperRater.com |website=[[MarketWatch]] |date=August 22, 2018 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Book Stacks Unlimited]]\n* [[Bookselling]]\n* [[List of book distributors]]\n* [[List of bookstore chains]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Books|Companies|New York City}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|author=Kirkpatrick, David D.|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/bizfinance/biz/features/47/ |title=Barnes & Noble's Jekyll and Hyde|magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York magazine]] |date= July 19, 1999}}\n* {{cite news|author=Trachtenberg, Jeffrey A.|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303626804579507321532982730?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10001424052702303626804579507321532982730.html |title=What's Barnes & Noble's Survival Plan? Former CEO Cuts Holding to 20%, but Says, 'The Story Isn't Written Yet'|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= April 18, 2014|url-access=subscription}}\n* {{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iuct6UkKs7o|title=The Rise And Fall Of Barnes & Noble|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2018-11-08}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Barnes & Noble}}\n* {{official website}}\n* [http://www.secdatabase.com/CIK/890491/Company-Name/BARNES-%26-NOBLE-INC Barnes & Noble SEC Filing]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101101215022/http://mainstore.bncollege.com/ Barnes & Noble at 18th Street Bookstore (flagship store)]\n\n{{Bookstore Chains}}\n{{ebooks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes and Noble}}\n[[Category:Barnes & Noble| ]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2019 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1917]]\n[[Category:Book selling websites]]\n[[Category:Bookstores established in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Bookstores in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Bookstores of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:E-book suppliers]]\n[[Category:Music retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Online retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Private equity portfolio companies]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1917]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American bookseller and retailer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{stack begin}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Barnes & Noble, Inc.\n| logo = Barnes & Noble logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| ISIN = US0677741094\n| predecessor = Arthur Hinds & Company\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1886}} (as Arthur Hinds & Company)<br>[[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| founders = Charles M. Barnes<br />William Barnes<br />G. Clifford Noble<br />[[Leonard Riggio]]<ref name=\"water_stones\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/07/books/barnes-noble-sale.html |last=Alter  |first=Alexandra |last2=Hsu  |first2=Tiffany |date=June 7, 2019 |title=Barnes & Noble Is Sold to Hedge Fund After a Tumultuous Year |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"imprint\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/05/07/476931295/barnes-noble-founder-retires-leaving-his-imprint-on-bookstores-history |date=May 7, 2016 |title=Barnes & Noble Founder Retires, Leaving His Imprint On Bookstore's History |work=[[NPR]]|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| location_city = New York City, New York\n| location_country = U.S.\n| locations = 627 retail stores<br>({{as of|2019|3|7|df=US}})<ref name=\"fiscal2019-3rdqtr\">{{cite press release |url=http://investors.barnesandnobleinc.com/news-releases/news-release-details/barnes-noble-reports-fiscal-2019-third-quarter-results |title=Barnes & Noble Reports Fiscal 2019 Third Quarter Results |work=Barnes & Noble |date=March 7, 2019}}</ref>\n| key_people = Leonard Riggio ([[Chairperson|Chairman]]),<br>[[James Daunt]] ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| products = [[Barnes & Noble Nook|Nook]]<br>[[SparkNotes]]\n| brands = '''Barnes & Noble Booksellers'''<br />'''Nook Digital, LLC'''<br />'''Sterling Publishing'''\n| revenue = {{decrease}} [[US$]] 3.552 billion (FY 2019)\n| operating_income = {{increase}} US$ 38.596 million (FY 2019)\n| net_income = {{decrease}} US$ 3.769 million (FY 2019)\n| assets = {{steady}} US$ 1.705 billion (FY 2019)\n| equity = {{steady}} US$ 444.497 million (FY 2019)\n| num_employees = 24,000 (2019) \n| slogan = \n| owner = Public company / Leonard Riggio - largest shareholder (11.8%)\n| parent = [[Elliott Management Corporation]]\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/}} (corporate site)<br />{{URL|http://www.barnesandnoble.com/}} (consumer site)<br /> {{URL|http://www.nook.com/}} (consumer site)\n| footnotes= <ref>{{cite web|url=https://wallmine.com/nyse/bks|date=July 29, 2019|title=Barnes & Noble|work=wallmine|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{stack end}}\n'''Barnes & Noble, Inc.''', is an American bookseller. It is a [[Fortune 1000]] company and the bookseller with the largest number of retail outlets in the United States. As of March 7, 2019, the company operates 627 retail stores in all 50 [[U.S. states]].<ref name=\"fiscal2019-3rdqtr\" /> In August 2019, [[Elliott Management Corporation]] acquired the company.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190807005399/en/Elliott-Completes-Acquisition-Barnes-Noble | title=Elliott Completes Acquisition of Barnes & Noble | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBarnes & Noble operates mainly through its Barnes & Noble Booksellers chain of [[bookstore]]s. The company's headquarters are at 122 [[Fifth Avenue]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/sponsorship/sponsorships_national/donations_national.html|title=National Sponsorships and Donations|accessdate=January 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121101559/http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/sponsorship/sponsorships_national/donations_national.html|archive-date=January 21, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter a series of mergers and bankruptcies in the American bookstore industry since the 1990s, Barnes & Noble stands alone as the United States' largest national bookstore chain.<ref name=\"wp\">{{cite web|last=DePillis|first=Lydia|title=Barnes & Noble's troubles don't show why bookstores are doomed. They show how they'll survive.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/07/10/barnes-nobles-troubles-dont-show-why-its-doomed-they-show-how-it-survives/|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 30, 2013|date=July 10, 2013|quote=it's now the only national bookstore chain in the country}}</ref><ref name=\"bw\">{{cite web|last=Townsend |first=Matt |title=Bookstores Not Dead Yet as Riggio Bets on Barnes & Noble |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2013-07-10/bookstores-not-dead-yet-as-riggio-bets-on-barnes-and-noble |work=Bloomberg Businessweek |accessdate=October 30, 2013 |date=July 10, 2013 |quote=the last national bookstore chain |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130916111734/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2013-07-10/bookstores-not-dead-yet-as-riggio-bets-on-barnes-and-noble |archivedate=September 16, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> Previously, Barnes & Noble operated the chain of small [[B. Dalton|B. Dalton Bookseller]] stores in malls until they announced the liquidation of the chain. The company was also one of the nation's largest manager of college textbook stores located on or near many college campuses when that division was spun off as a separate public company called [[#Barnes & Noble Education|Barnes & Noble Education]] in 2015.\n\nThe company is known by its customers for large retail outlets, many of which contain a [[caf\u00e9]] serving [[Starbucks]] [[coffee]] and other consumables. Most stores sell books, magazines, newspapers, DVDs, graphic novels, gifts, games, toys, music, and [[Barnes & Noble Nook|Nook]]&nbsp;[[e-reader|e&#8209;reader]]s and [[tablet computer|tablets]].\n\n==History==\n===19th century: Foundations===\n[[File:Clifford Noble in 1893.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Clifford Noble in 1893]]\nBarnes & Noble began in 1886 as a bookstore called '''Arthur Hinds & Company''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/shephyken/2018/04/08/arming-the-davids-of-industry-against-disruptive-goliaths/#6fd75b466c84 |last=Hyken |first=Shep |date=April 8, 2018 |title=Barnes & Noble, Amazon, Independents: Who's Disrupting Whom? |work=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=September 8, 2019}}</ref> located in the Cooper Union Building in [[New York City]].<ref>\"Barnes & Noble to Move.\" The Bookseller and Stationer, January 1. 1922 p. 13</ref><ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|0595374786}}, 9780595374786 page 71</ref> In the fall of 1886, Gilbert Clifford Noble, a then-recent [[Harvard University|Harvard]] graduate from [[Westfield, Massachusetts]], was hired to work there as a clerk.<ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|0595374786}}, 9780595374786 page 65</ref> \n\nIn 1894, Noble was made a partner, and the name of the shop was changed to Hinds & Noble.<ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|0595374786}}, 9780595374786 page 101</ref> \n\n===20th century: Expansion===\n====1900\u20131919====\nIn 1901, Hinds & Noble moved to 31\u201335 W. 15th Street.<ref>\"Barnes & Noble to Move.\" ''The Bookseller and Stationer'', January 1. 1922 p. 13</ref>\n\nIn 1917, Noble bought out Hinds and entered into a partnership with William Barnes, son of his old friend Charles Barnes; the name of the store was changed to Barnes & Noble soon after.<ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|0595374786}}, 9780595374786 page 151</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Cynthia |last=Blair |title=1917: First Barnes & Noble Bookstore Opens in Manhattan |url=http://www.newsday.com/about/ny-ihiny021705story,0,5026610.htmlstory |newspaper=[[Newsday]] |accessdate=2007-08-01 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001000727/http://www.newsday.com/about/ny-ihiny021705story%2C0%2C5026610.htmlstory |archivedate=October 1, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> Charles had previously opened a book-printing business in [[Wheaton, Illinois]] in 1873, named the C. M. Barnes-Wilcox Company; William Barnes, however, divested himself of his ownership interest in his father's business shortly before his partnership with Noble. (His father's company would go on to become the [[Follett Corporation]].) Although the flagship store once featured the motto \"Founded in 1873,\" the C. M. Barnes-Wilcox Company never had any connection with Barnes & Noble, save for the fact that both were partly owned (at different times) by William Barnes.\n\n====1920\u20131939====\n[[File:Barnes & Noble Fifth Ave flagship.jpg|thumb|right|Barnes & Noble's former flagship store at 105 [[Fifth Avenue]] in [[Manhattan]], New York, that operated from 1932 to 2014.]]\n\nIn 1930, Noble sold his share of the company to William Barnes' son, John Wilcox Barnes.<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 62\">''The Late Age of Print: Everyday Book Culture from Consumerism to Control'' by Theodore G. Striphas. Columbia University Press: 2009. 978-0-231-14814-6 p. 62</ref> Noble died on June 6, 1936, at the age of 72.<ref>''The Noble Legacy: The Story of Gilbert Clifford Noble, Cofounder of the Barnes & Noble and Noble & Noble Book Companies'' by Betty N. Turner. iUniverse: 2006 {{ISBN|9780595374786}} page 153</ref> In 1932, at the height of the [[Great Depression]], the bookstore moved its flagship location to 18th Street and [[Fifth Avenue]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tmHEm5ohoCUC&pg=PA1266&dq=%22flagship+store%22+1932+barnes+noble&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WNETUuC3NMjnqAGThoGoBw&ved=0CFAQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22flagship%20store%22%201932%20barnes%20noble&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of New York State|editor=Eisenstadt, Peter|work=Syracuse University Press|page=1266|year=2004}}</ref> which served as the company's flagship location until its closure in 2014. The Noble family retained ownership of an associated publishing business, and Barnes & Noble opened a new publishing division in 1931.<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 62\"/>\n\n====1940\u20131959====\nIn 1940, the store was one of the first businesses to feature [[Muzak Holdings|Muzak]] and it underwent a major renovation the following year.<ref>''The Late Age of Print: Everyday Book Culture from Consumerism to Control'' by Theodore G. Striphas. Columbia University Press: 2009. 978-0-231-14814-6 p. 64</ref> That decade the company opened stores in Brooklyn and Chicago.<ref name=\"Barnes pg 78\">''Barnes & Noble: Groundbreaking Entrepreneurs'' by Kayla Morgan. Abdo Publishing: 2000 {{ISBN|9781604537581}} p. 78</ref> William Barnes died in 1945, at the age of 78, and his son John Wilcox Barnes assumed full control.<ref name=\"Barnes pg 78\"/>  The company underwent a significant expansion between the 1950s and the 1960s, opening an additional retail store on 23rd Street in Manhattan, as well as shops near the City University of New York, Harvard, and other Northeast college campuses.<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 65\">''The Late Age of Print: Everyday Book Culture from Consumerism to Control'' by Theodore G. Striphas. Columbia University Press: 2009. 978-0-231-14814-6 p. 65</ref>\n\n====1960\u20131979====\n[[File:122 Fifth Avenue.jpg|left|thumb|167px|Barnes & Noble corporate headquarters, 122 (122\u2013124) Fifth Avenue between West 17th and 18th Streets in the Flatiron District neighborhood of Manhattan, New York City]]\n[[File:Barnes & Noble sign.jpg|thumb|right|200px|5th Avenue store sign]]\nJohn Barnes died in 1964, and the company was sold to the conglomerate Amtel two years later.<ref>''Reluctant Capitalists: Bookselling and the Culture of Consumption'' by Laura J. Miller.  University Of Chicago Press: 2007 p. 47</ref> The business was then purchased in 1971 by [[Leonard Riggio]], who has been credited as one of the founders,<ref name=\"water_stones\"/><ref name=\"imprint\"/> for $1.2 million.<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 65\"/> By then, it had been mismanaged and consisted only of \"a significantly reduced wholesale operation and a single retail location\u2014the flagship store at 105 Fifth Avenue.\"<ref name=\"Print 2009. pg 65\"/> The publishing operation was sold separately by Amtel to [[Harper & Row]].<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Gale Research Company| isbn = 0-8103-1724-9| volume = 46| pages = [https://archive.org/details/americanliterary0046unse/page/40 40]| editor = Peter Dzwonkoski| last = Wilkinson| first = Carol| title = American literary publishing houses, 1900-1980. edited by Peter Dzwonkoski.| chapter = Barnes & Noble Books| location = Detroit, Mich.| series = Dictionary of literary biography| date = 1986| url = https://archive.org/details/americanliterary0046unse/page/40}}</ref> In 1974, Barnes & Noble became the first bookstore chain to advertise on television and a year later, the company became the first bookseller in the United States to discount books, by selling ''[[The New York Times]]'' best-selling titles at 40% off the publishers' list price.<ref name=hist>{{Cite journal|title=Barnes & Noble History |url=http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/history/bn_history.html#H3 |accessdate=2008-06-13 |publisher=Barnes &amp; Noble |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509130810/http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/history/bn_history.html |archivedate=May 9, 2008 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> Between the 1970s and the 1980s, Barnes & Noble opened smaller discount stores, which were eventually phased out in favor of larger stores. They also began to publish their own books to be sold to mail-order customers. These titles were primarily affordable reissues of out-of-print titles and selling them through mail-order catalogs allowed Barnes & Noble to reach new customers nationwide.<ref name=hist />\n\nIn November 1974, editors of the British-produced ''[[Guinness Book of Records]]'', claimed on the [[BBC One]] television programme [[Record Breakers]] that the Fifth Avenue store of Barnes & Noble had overtaken that of London's [[Foyles]] bookshop to become the world's biggest bookstore.<ref>''Record Breakers''. Presented by Roy Castle. Co-presented by Norris and Ross McWhirter. BBC 1. Broadcast on Tuesday November 19, 1974.</ref>\n\n====1980\u20131999====\nBarnes & Noble continued to expand throughout the 1980s, and it purchased the primarily [[shopping mall]]-based [[B. Dalton]] chain from [[Dayton Hudson]] in 1986, for an estimated $275 million to $300 million.<ref name=bloomberg>{{cite news|first=Stephen|last=Miller |title=Bruce Dayton, CEO of Retailer That Became Target, Dies at 97 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-11-13/bruce-dayton-who-led-family-s-dayton-hudson-stores-dies-at-97 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=2015-10-13 |accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref> Solveig Robinson, author of ''The Book in Society: An Introduction to Print Culture'', wrote that the purchase \"gave [Barnes & Noble] the necessary know-how and infrastructure to create what, in 1992, became the definitive bookselling superstore.\"<ref>Robinson, Solveig. ''The Book in Society: An Introduction to Print Culture''. [[Broadview Press]], November 15, 2013. {{ISBN|1770484310}}, 9781770484313. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=qfKuAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA260 260].</ref> The acquisition of the 797 B. Dalton bookstores turned the company into a nationwide retailer, and by the end of fiscal year 1999, the second-largest online bookseller in the United States.<ref name=\"BIannual1999\">{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/for_investors/annual_reports/bnannual99.pdf|title=BarnesAndNobleInc.com|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-09-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116003831/http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/for_investors/annual_reports/bnannual99.pdf|archive-date=January 16, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> B&N's critics claim that it has contributed to the decline of local and independent booksellers.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Warren |last=St. John |title=Barnes & Noble's Epiphany |url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/7.06/barnes.html |date=July 6, 1999 |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=2008-05-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506092855/http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/7.06/barnes.html |archivedate=May 6, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> The last B. Dalton stores were scheduled to close in January 2010.<ref name=\"BIannual1999\" />  \n\nIn 1989, Barnes & Noble purchased the 22-store chain [[Bookstop (company)|Bookstop]].\n\nIn September 1993, Barnes & Noble became a publicly traded company by issuing $77 million worth of stock on the New York Stock Exchange under the BKS ticker symbol.<ref name=\"nyt-1993sep03\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/03/business/barnes-noble-goes-public-vol-2.html?pagewanted=all |title=Barnes & Noble Goes Public: Vol. 2 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 3, 1993 |first=Stephanie |last=Strom |page=D1}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-1993sep28\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/28/business/company-news-barnes-noble-offering-price-rises-to-20-a-share.html?pagewanted=all |title=Barnes & Noble Offering Price Rises to $20 A Share |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 28, 1993 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |page=D4}}</ref> The company remained on the stock exchange until August 2019 when Elliot Management purchased all of the company's stock and took the company private.\n\nBefore Barnes & Noble created its official website, it sold books directly to customers through mail-order catalogs. It first began selling books online through an early [[videotex]] service called \"[[Prodigy (online service)|Trintex]],\" a joint venture between [[Sears]] and [[IBM]], but the company's website was not launched until May 1997.<ref name=BNSiteHistory /> BarnesandNoble.com went public in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/1999/05/24/technology/barnesandnoble/|title=Barnesandnoble sets IPO at $18  - May 24, 1999|website=money.cnn.com|access-date=2018-08-22}}</ref>\n\n===21st century: Operating in an electronic environment===\n====2000s====\nIn 2004, it was reported that the reading of books was on the decline in America, with the number of non-reading adults increasing by 17 million between 1992 and 2002. Despite this, Barnes & Noble claimed that its retail store business was expanding in the book market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/huge-decline-in-book-reading/|title=Huge Decline In Book Reading|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref> Beginning in 1999, Barnes & Noble owned [[GameStop]], a video game and electronics retail outlet. The company distributed its shares in GameStop in late 2004, spinning it off into its own company in an attempt to simplify its corporate structure.<ref>{{cite news|title=Barnes & Noble Pares GameStop |author=Jeffrey A. Trachtenberg|date=October 5, 2004 |work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\nCEO Leonard Riggio stepped down in 2002, naming his younger brother and former acting chief executive of BarnesandNoble.com, Stephen Riggio, to succeed him. Some corporate governance experts noted that this appointment could potentially cause conflict of interest, but the company board noted that Riggio's experience at the company made him the right person for the job.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/14/business/shifting-leadership-bookseller-barnes-noble-chief-steps-aside-for-brother.html|title=A Shifting Of Leadership At Bookseller; Barnes & Noble Chief Steps Aside for Brother|last=Kirkpatrick|first=David D.|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref> Stephen Riggio stepped down from the position in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/03/18/barnes-nobles-ceo-steps-down-bn-com-president-william-lynch-takes-over/|title=Barnes & Noble CEO Steps Down, BN.com President William Lynch Takes Over|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n====2010s====\nIn 2010, website president William Lynch was named CEO. He is credited with helping launch the company's [[electronic book]] store and overseeing the introduction of its [[e-reader|electronic book reader]], the [[Nook]]. Many observers saw his appointment as underscoring the importance of digital books to Barnes & Noble's future. Steve Riggio stayed on as vice chairman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/companies/management/2010-03-18-barnes-and-noble-execs_N.htm |title=Barnes & Noble names website head William Lynch as CEO|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date= March 18, 2010}}</ref>  When Lynch resigned in mid-2013,<ref>{{cite web|author=Brown, Abram|title=Barnes & Noble CEO Lynch Out After Nook Woes Deepen|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/abrambrown/2013/07/08/barnes-noble-ceo-lynch-out-after-kindle-woes-deepen/|work=Forbes|date=July 8, 2013|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> he was replaced by Chief Financial Officer Michael Huseby early the next year.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.marketwatch.com/story/barnes-noble-appoints-michael-p-huseby-chief-executive-officer-2014-01-08|publisher=Market Watch|title=Barnes & Noble points Michael P. Huseby CEO|date=January 8, 2014 }}</ref> Following the spinoff of Barnes & Noble Education, Huseby departed to head the new firm; his place was filled in mid-2015 by Ronald Boire,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/business/media/barnes-noble-names-ronald-boire-of-sears-canada-ceo.html|title=Barnes &amp; Noble Names Ronald Boire of Sears Canada as C.E.O.|date=July 3, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Barnes & Noble Completes Spin-Off of Barnes & Noble Education|url=http://next.bncollege.com/barnes-noble-completes-spin-off-of-barnes-noble-education/}}</ref> who departed one year later.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barnes & Noble Says CEO Boire 'Not a Good Fit' and Will Step Down|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/barnes-noble-ceo-ronald-boire-is-leaving-1471380961|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Demos Parneros was named Barnes & Noble's Chief Executive Officer in April 2017 after having joined the company as Chief Operating Officer in November 2016; however, he was fired in July 2018 for \"company policy violations\" without severance and was immediately removed from the company's board, at the advice of a law firm hired by Barnes & Noble.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/07/03/news/companies/barnes-noble-fires-ceo/index.html|title=Barnes & Noble fires CEO for violating company policy|last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=2018-07-03|work=[[CNNMoney]]|access-date=2018-07-04}}</ref> On August 28, 2018, Parneros filed a lawsuit against Barnes & Noble, claiming wrongful termination.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/work/1372756/fired-barnes-noble-ceo-demos-parneros-sues-for-wrongful-termination/|title=A lawsuit by a fired Barnes & Noble CEO is a spectacular example of not going quietly|work=Quartz at Work|access-date=2018-08-30|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nAfter the bankruptcy and closure of its chief competitor, [[Borders Group]], in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|last=Leopold|first=Todd|title=The death and life of a great American bookstore|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/09/12/first.borders.bookstore.closing/|work=CNN|accessdate=October 30, 2013|date=September 12, 2011}}</ref> Barnes & Noble became the last remaining national bookstore chain in the United States.<ref name=\"wp\"/><ref name=\"bw\"/> This followed a series of mergers and bankruptcies in the American bookstore industry since the 1990s, which also saw the demise of [[Waldenbooks]], Barnes & Noble's own subsidiary [[B. Dalton]], and [[Crown Books]], among others. Barnes & Noble's largest physical bookstore rival is now [[Books-A-Million]], which does not operate in the Western US. Barnes & Noble also faces competition from general retailers, especially from [[Amazon.com]], and from regional and independent booksellers. Amazon has even opened its own physical bookstores, once again creating a second national bookstore chain.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/bea/article/73837-bookexpo-2017-amazon-will-be-the-fifth-largest-bookstore-chain.html|title=Amazon Will Be the Fifth Largest Bookstore Chain|magazine=Publisher's Weekly|date=June 1, 2017|accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBarnes & Noble began reducing its overall presence in the 2010s, closing its original flagship store in early 2014.<ref name=\"crains\">{{cite news |first=Adrianne |last=Pasquarelli |authorlink= |title=Barnes & Noble closes the book on Fifth Ave. store |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20140107/RETAIL_APPAREL/140109914 |work=[[Crain Communications|Crain's New York Business]] |date=January 7, 2014 | page= |accessdate=2015-09-01}}</ref> In mid-2014, the company announced it would separate its Nook Media division from its retail store division.<ref name=\"Franzen, Carl\">{{cite web|author=Franzen, Carl|title=Barnes & Noble is splitting into two companies: one for Nooks and one for books|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/6/25/5841278/barnes-noble-is-splitting-into-two-companies-nook-and-books}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Barnes & Noble permanently laid off 1,800 full time employees at an annual cost savings of $40 million per year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/13/barnes-noble-confirms-job-cuts-expects-40-million-in-cost-savings.html|title=Barnes & Noble confirms job cuts, expects $40 million in annual cost savings|last=Thomas|first=Lauren|date=2018-02-13|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-08-22}}</ref> According to ''[[TechCrunch]]'', the company essentially fired their entire full time staff at all their stores, who would be making an average of $22,000 per year (~$11 per hour), and were replaced by part time workers earning close to minimum wage.<ref name=\"techcrunch-2018feb16\">{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/02/16/barnes-noble-is-killing-itself/ |title=Barnes & Noble is killing itself |website=[[TechCrunch]] |date=February 16, 2018 |first=John |last=Biggs}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 fiscal year that ended in July, the company overall losses reached $17 million.<ref name=\"forbes-2018sep06\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andriacheng/2018/09/06/barnes-nobles-problem-is-no-longer-about-amazon/#9d2398244d08 |title=Barnes & Noble's Problem Is No Longer Just Amazon |magazine=[[Forbes]] |date=September 6, 2018 |first=Andria |last=Cheng}}</ref> \n\nIn early July 2018, Barnes & Noble fired CEO Demos Parneros for an unspecified violation of company policy, which was later revealed to be over sexual harassment claims.<ref>{{cite news|author=Meyersohn, Nathaniel|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/09/06/news/companies/barnes-and-noble-books-amazon/index.html|title=Barnes & Noble is overrun with problems|date=2018-09-06|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=2019-11-15|language=en-US}}</ref> It accused Pareneros of breaching his duties of loyalty and good faith and acting as a \"[[faithless servant]]\" by sexually harassing the female employee, bullying subordinates, and attempting to \"sabotage\" a potential acquisition of the New York-based company, and asserted that the company should therefore be entitled to [[claw back]] his salary, bonus, and other benefits during the period of his \"disloyal conduct\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/barnes-noble-lawsuit/corrected-barnes-noble-countersues-ex-ceo-it-fired-after-alleged-harassment-idUSL2N1XA25U|last=Stempel |first=Jonathan |date=October 30, 2018|title=-Barnes & Noble countersues ex-CEO it fired after alleged harassment|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 2018, the board of directors announced that they would entertain offers to buy the company. Among the potential buyers was Leonard Riggio, who owns approximately 19% of Barnes & Noble stock. As a result of the news, the company's stock price jumped by nearly 30%.<ref name=\"fm-2018oct03\">{{cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2018/10/03/barnes-noble-sale/ |title=Barnes & Noble Considers Selling Itself Yet Again |magazine=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune Magazine]] |date=October 3, 2018 |first=Phil |last=Wahba}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, [[Elliott Management Corporation]] acquired the company<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190807005399/en/Elliott-Completes-Acquisition-Barnes-Noble | title=Elliott Completes Acquisition of Barnes & Noble | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | date=August 7, 2019}}</ref> for approximately $683m with [[James Daunt]], the [[managing director]] of [[London]]-based [[Waterstones|Waterstones Booksellers Ltd.]], becoming CEO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/elliott-buy-barnes-noble-daunt-will-run-both-chains-1020446|last=Jones |first=Philip |date=June 7, 2019|title=Elliott to buy Barnes & Noble; Daunt will run both chains|work=[[The Bookseller website]]}}</ref>\n\n==Publishing==<!-- This section is linked from [[Nine Men's Morris]] -->\nBarnes & Noble maintains a separate publishing business in addition to its retail stores and other entities. Barnes & Noble's publishing company got its start by reissuing inexpensive versions of out-of-print books, and made a push to expand the unit in 2003. The company saw success the following year; in September 2004, its book, \"Hippie,\" reached [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/09/books/huge-book-retailer-expands-its-publishing-role.html?mtrref=www.google.com|title=Huge Book Retailer Expands Its Publishing Role|last=Wyatt|first=Edward|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref> \n\nBarnes & Noble often publishes and sells books at a lower cost than competitors, and sells lines of inexpensive books like Barnes & Noble Classics.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition, the company has a second paperback series called the ''Barnes & Noble Library of Essential Reading''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/u/Barnes-and-Noble-Library-of-Essential-Readings/379001270/|title=Barnes & Noble Library of Essential Reading|publisher=Barnes & Noble|accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref>Barnes & Noble's edition of ''The Gentle Art of Verbal Self-Defense'' by [[Suzette Haden Elgin]], has sold over 250,000 copies,<ref name=BNSiteHistory /> and its reissued edition of ''The Columbia History of the World'' by John Garrity, has sold over 1 million copies.<ref name=BNSiteHistory>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnobleinc.com/our_company/history/bn_history.html |title=Barnes & Noble History|website= Barnes & Noble Inc.|accessdate= September 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/8527098/Barnes-and-Noble-a-history.html|title=Barnes & Noble: a history|date=2011-05-20|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThe company has expanded business by acquiring several firms over the years, including J.B. Fairfax International in 1999<ref>{{Cite web| title = B&N Buys J.B. Fairfax International| work = PublishersWeekly.com| accessdate = 2020-03-28| url = https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/19990816/39525-b-amp-n-buys-j-b-fairfax-international.html}}</ref>, [[SparkNotes]], an educational website and publishing company, in 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sec.edgar-online.com/2001/06/18/0000950123-01-503532/Section2.asp |title=Barnes & Noble inc - BKS Quarterly Report (10-Q) Item 1: Financial Statements |accessdate=2008-02-05 |date=18 June 2001 |publisher=Edgar Online |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224133049/http://sec.edgar-online.com/2001/06/18/0000950123-01-503532/Section2.asp |archivedate=December 24, 2007 }}</ref> and [[Sterling Publishing]] in 2003.<ref name=BNSiteHistory/>\n\n==Food service==\n[[File:6.25.11SpringfieldBarnes&NobleByLuigiNovi.jpg|thumb|left|The Barnes & Noble caf\u00e9 in [[Springfield Township, Union County, New Jersey|Springfield, New Jersey]]]]\nIn 1993, Barnes & Noble signed an agreement to serve Starbucks coffee in each of its existing and future cafes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930907&slug=1719818|title=Business {{!}} Starbucks Co. Books Space In Barnes & Noble Chain {{!}} Seattle Times Newspaper|website=community.seattletimes.nwsource.com|access-date=2018-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.strategy-business.com/article/20534?gko=582b3|title=The Barista Principle \u2014 Starbucks and the Rise of Relational Capital|last=Neilson|first=Ranjay Gulati, Sarah Huffman, and Gary L.|work=strategy+business|access-date=2017-08-09}}</ref> In 2004, Barnes & Noble began offering [[Wi-Fi]] in the caf\u00e9 area of selected stores, using SBC FreedomLink (now the [[AT&T Inc.|AT&T]] Wi-Fi network). All stores offered Wi-Fi as of 2006 and as of July 27, 2009, Wi-Fi is offered for free to all customers.<ref>Colker, David. [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/technology/2009/07/free-wifi-barnes-nobel-starbucks-att.html \"Internet wants to be free at Barnes & Noble\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', July 29, 2009</ref>[[File:Barnes & Noble Interior.JPG|thumb|right|The Barnes & Noble at [[The Grove at Farmers Market]], [[Los Angeles]].]]\n[[Image:Bnlynnwood.jpg|thumb|right|Barnes & Noble in [[Lynnwood, Washington]], using the former 1990s era logo.]]\n\nIn 2016, Barnes & Noble announced plans to open four concept stores in 2017 that featured caf\u00e9s twice the size of its usual food spots, as well as bars offering wine and beer. Restaurants would also include a waitstaff and a full menu for breakfast, lunch, and dinner. The restaurants were expected to revive sales growth. Company executives planned to open additional concept stores if sales met expectations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2016/06/23/barnes-and-noble-wine/|title=Cheers? Barnes & Noble Is Getting Into the Bars and Restaurant Business|work=Fortune|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref> The first stores were opened in [[Scarsdale, New York]], [[Edina, Minnesota]], [[Plano, Texas]], and [[Folsom, California]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nrn.com/casual-dining/barnes-noble-continues-expand-full-service-kitchen|title=Barnes & Noble continues to expand full-service Kitchen|date=2017-11-10|work=Nation's Restaurant News|access-date=2018-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Community involvement==\nBarnes & Noble hires community business development managers to engage in community outreach.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsminer.com/readers_choice/barnes-noble-voted-best-local-bookstore/article_c43a032c-920a-11e8-97f6-fff74df2cd9d.html|title=Barnes & Noble voted best local bookstore|last=intern|first=David Jones, News-Miner|work=Fairbanks Daily News-Miner|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/chattanooganow/outabout/story/2018/aug/08/pick-page-turner-book-sellers-name-their-summ/476528/|title=Pick up a page-turner: Book-sellers name their summer reading picks|last=|first=|date=8 August 2018|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Barnes & Noble also gives back to the community to increase literacy and education. The Barnes & Noble located in Fairbanks, Alaska gave over $80,000 to the community between 2015 and 2018 through book fair fundraising programs.<ref name=\":1\" /> To promote nationwide literacy among 1st through 6th graders and encourage more reading during the summer, Barnes & Noble has implemented a summer challenge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/summerreading/|title=Summer Reading Challenge|work=Barnes & Noble website |accessdate=2009-05-08| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430094614/http://www.barnesandnoble.com/summerreading/| archivedate=April 30, 2009 | url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fool.com/earnings/call-transcripts/2018/06/22/barnes-noble-bks-q4-2018-earnings-conference-call.aspx|title=Barnes & Noble (BKS) Q4 2018 Earnings Conference Call Transcript|last=Staff|first=Motley Fool|work=The Motley Fool|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/ads/other/ads/fun-stuff-for-kids-online/ad_c0b49d72-9672-11e8-9b90-9b4fe3103637.html|title=Fun Stuff for Kids Online|website=Sioux City Journal|language=en|access-date=2018-08-31}}</ref>\n\n== ''The Barnes & Noble Review'' ==\n'''''The Barnes & Noble Review''''' is an [[online magazine]], hosted on Barnes & Noble's website, that publishes evaluations of both fiction and nonfiction works, along with essays, interviews, and pieces on other topics. It was launched in October 2007 by Barnes & Noble CEO Steve Riggio and [[James Mustich, Jr.]], publisher of the book catalog [[A Common Reader]]. Regular contributors to the magazine have included book critics [[Michael Dirda]], Brooke Allen, Laura Miller, and [[Adam Kirsch]], as well as prominent writers in fields outside of literary criticism, such as political journalists [[Chris Hayes]] and [[Ezra Klein]], philosopher [[A.\u2009C. Grayling]], music critic [[Robert Christgau]], and cartoonist [[Ward Sutton]]. Miller, who has written for ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' and Mustich's Common Reader, said, \"The reviews [at ''BNR''] are the same as anywhere else\", adding that the tone and length of the pieces evoke ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' rather than the less formal ''Salon''. The magazine's [[web traffic]] flourished during its first few years. According to [[Compete.com]], it amassed 50,000 [[unique user|unique visitors]] in December 2009.<ref name=\"CJR\">{{cite magazine|last=Smith|first=Jordan Michael|date=April 2010|url=https://archives.cjr.org/review/critical_condition.php|title=Critical Condition|magazine=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome critics were originally skeptical of ''The Barnes & Noble Review''. Art Winslow, former literary editor of ''[[The Nation]]'', said that because Barnes & Noble is a [[brand name]], ''BNR''{{'}}s contributors are effectively endorsing the corporation, and that the motives behind the publication undermine its integrity: \"Criticism's content should be free of any commercialism. Barnes & Noble has found another way to sell books, and that's the ''Review''. ... I wouldn't write there.\" Mustich disputed the idea that the magazine serves as a corporate tactic: \"We counter that skepticism with quality. If people read the site, they can determine that we are doing what we purport to do. They have never tried to influence my judgment. The first attempt would have been the last.\"<ref name=\"CJR\"/>\n\n==Barnes & Noble Nook==\n{{See also|Barnes & Noble Nook}}\nBarnes & Noble Nook (styled NOOK) is a suite of [[e-book]] readers developed by the company,<ref>{{cite news|author=Jeffrey A. Trachtenberg and Geoffrey A. Fowler|title=B&N Reader Out Tuesday|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703816204574483790552304348|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=October 20, 2009|accessdate=October 20, 2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091021225827/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703816204574483790552304348.html|archivedate=October 21, 2009|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref> based on the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] platform. The first device was announced in the [[United States]] on October 20, 2009 and was released November 30, 2009, for $259.<ref>{{cite web |author=Ina Fried|title=Barnes & Noble's 'Nook' said to cost $259|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13860_3-10378525-56.html|work=|publisher=[[CNET Networks|cnet news]]|date=October 19, 2009|accessdate=October 20, 2009}}</ref> On June 21, 2010, Barnes & Noble reduced the Nook's price to $199, as well as launched a new [[Wi-Fi]]-only model, for $149, and released a Nook colored touch screen for $249.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/06/21/tech/main6603068.shtml|work=[[CBS News]]| title=Barnes & Noble Cuts Nook Price|date=June 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Nook competes with the [[Amazon Kindle]], [[Kobo eReader]], and other e-reader offerings and color tablets with reading apps, such as Apple's [[iBooks]] for [[iOS]] devices. Various Nook models feature a 6-inch, 7-inch, or larger [[touchscreen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/nook/features/index.asp |website=Barnes & Noble|title=Nook Features}}</ref> Version 1.3 of the Nook introduced [[Wi-Fi]] connectivity, a web browser, a dictionary, [[chess]], and [[sudoku]] games, and a separate, smaller color touchscreen that serves as the primary input device. The Nook also features a Read in Store capability that allows visitors to stream and read any book for up to one hour while shopping in a Barnes & Noble bookstore. According to a June 2010 [[CNet]] article, the company planned to expand this feature to include periodicals in the near future.<ref>{{cite web |author=David Carnoy|title=B&N delivers meaty Nook update, teases iPad app|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17938_105-20003085-1.html|work=|publisher=[[CNET Networks|cnet news]]|date=April 23, 2010 |accessdate=June 7, 2010}}</ref> The [[Nook Color|color version of the Nook]] introduced a 7-inch color touchscreen and the ability to view at a portrait or landscape orientation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/nookcolor/features/index.asp |title=Nook Color Features|website= Barnes &. Noble|accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 2012, Microsoft invested $300 million for a 17.6% stake in Nook, which valued the business at about $1.7 billion.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ovide |first=Shira |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303916904577375502392129654 |title=Microsoft to Invest in Barnes & Noble's Nook |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=May 2, 2012 |accessdate=2012-09-18|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, the technology publications ''[[Mashable]]'' and ''[[Techdirt]]'' criticized the license agreement with which Barnes & Noble sells ebooks to consumers, pointing out that the rights to re-download a purchased ebook [[digital rights management|expire when the customer's credit card expires]], and a valid credit card must be added to the account to restore this functionality.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rosen, Kenneth |date=November 28, 2012|url=http://mashable.com/2012/11/28/barnes-and-noble-ereader/ |title=Barnes &amp; Noble: That Ebook is Only Yours Until Your Credit Card Expires|work= [[Mashable]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Cushing, Tim |date=November 27, 2012|url=http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20121126/18084721154/barnes-noble-decides-that-purchased-ebooks-are-only-yours-until-your-credit-card-expires.shtml |title=Barnes & Noble Decides That Purchased Ebooks Are Only Yours Until Your Credit Card Expires|work= [[Techdirt]]}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Barnes & Noble had previously announced that it would spin off its Nook Digital division into a separate publicly traded company,<ref name=\"Franzen, Carl\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-digital-reader.com/2015/02/26/bn-to-split-off-college-stores-retain-nook-and-retail-stores/|title= B&N to Split Off College Stores, Retain Nook and Retail Stores|work=The Digital Reader|accessdate= July 6, 2015|date=February 26, 2015}}</ref> but as of 2016, Nook remains a part of Barnes & Noble. That same month, the company announced a partnership with [[Samsung Electronics]] to make Nook tablets, as the bookseller moved forward with plans to revamp its digital business.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barnes & Noble Partners With Samsung to Make Nook Tablets|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/industries/2014/06/05/barnes-noble-to-develop-tablets-with-samsung/|work=FOXBusiness|date=June 5, 2014|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> Samsung and Barnes & Noble introduced the [[Samsung Galaxy Tab 4 Nook 7.0]] in August 2014, followed by the [[Samsung Galaxy Tab 4 Nook 10.1]] in October 2014. In December 2014, Barnes & Noble announced that it had ended its Nook partnership with Microsoft by buying back its stake.<ref>{{cite web|title=Microsoft, Barnes & Noble bring their weird Nook \"partnership\" to a formal end|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/12/microsoft-barnes-noble-bring-their-weird-nook-partnership-to-a-formal-end/|work=Ars Technica|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=December 26, 2014}}</ref> Samsung and Barnes & Noble continue to introduce new Nook tablets.<ref>{{cite news|work=PC Magazine|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2490627,00.asp|date=September 2015|title=Samsung and Barnes & Noble introduced the  Samsung Galaxy Tab S2 NOOK}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Barnes & Noble announced it would close the Nook App Store and Nook Video and in the UK close the Nook Store on March 15.<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2016/3/4/11160942/barnes-noble-nook-app-store-shutting-down-march-15th Barnes & Noble is shutting down the Nook App Store on March 15th] Retrieved March 4, 2016.</ref> It will continue to sell e-books as well as digital magazines and newspapers in the US.\n\n=={{anchor|Barnes & Noble Education}}College bookstores==\n{{See also|Barnes & Noble College Booksellers}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Barnes & Noble Education, Inc.\n| logo             = <!-- PLEASE ADD LOGO HERE -->\n| logo_size        = \n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = {{nyse|BNED}}\n| predecessor      = [[Corporate spin-off]] from Barnes & Noble, Inc.\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|2015|08|03}}\n| location_city    = [[Basking Ridge, New Jersey]]\n| location_country = United States\n| locations        = 773 (December 2018)<ref name=\"bw-2018dec04\" />\n| key_people       = Michael P. Huseby (CEO, chairman)\n| products         = \n| brands           = Yuzu digital textbook platform\n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| num_employees    = \n| divisions        = {{ublist|[[Barnes & Noble College Booksellers]]|MBS Textbook Exchange|Digital Student Solutions}}\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.bned.com/}}\n}}\n\nIn February 2015, Barnes & Noble had announced plans to spin off its college bookstore assets and create a separate company called Barnes & Noble Education.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2015/02/26/barnes-noble-college-spinoff/|title=Barnes & Noble is spinning off its college store business |magazine=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |access-date=2018-08-30 |first=John |last=Kell |date=February 26, 2015}}</ref> On August 3, 2015, Barnes & Noble Education, Inc. began trading on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] under the [[ticker symbol]], \"BNED\".<ref name=\"thestreet.com-2015aug03\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thestreet.com/story/13241726/1/barnes-and-noble-education-spins-off-looks-for-growth-in-digital-textbooks-colleges.html |title=Barnes and Noble Education Spins Off, Looks for Growth in Digital Textbooks, Colleges: Barnes and Noble Education rang the opening bell at the New York Stock Exchange after spinning off from Barnes and Noble, and will have its own board and management team. |website=[[TheStreet.com]] |date=August 3, 2015 |first=Rhonda |last=Schaffler}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/08/30/barnes-noble-education-shares-plunge-earnings-miss/615691001/ |title=Barnes & Noble Education shares plunge on earnings miss |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |access-date=2018-08-30 |first=Kevin |last=McCoy |date=August 30, 2017}}</ref> The company operated stores dedicated to selling college textbooks, both on and off campus.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[Crain's New York]] |url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20140107/RETAIL_APPAREL/140109914/barnes-noble-closes-the-book-on-fifth-ave-store |title=Barnes & Noble closes the book on Fifth Avenue Store |date=January 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Barnes & Noble Education had acquired MBS Textbook Exchange, a major textbook distributor based in [[Columbia, Missouri]], for $174.2 million in cash.<ref name=\"kbia-2017mar01\">{{cite news |url=http://www.kbia.org/post/barnes-and-noble-education-buys-mbs-textbook-exchange |title=Barnes and Noble Education Buys MBS Textbook Exchange |website=[[KBIA]] |date=March 1, 2017 |first=Beatriz Costa |last=Lima}}</ref><ref name=\"bw-2017feb28\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20170228005977/en/Barnes-Noble-Education-Acquires-MBS-174.2-Million |title=Barnes & Noble Education Acquires MBS for $174.2 Million |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=February 28, 2017 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\nBy December 2018, Barnes & Noble Education had operated or managed 773 campus bookstores under contracts.<ref name=\"bw-2018dec04\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20181204005215/en/Barnes-Noble-Education-Reports-Quarter-Fiscal-Year |title=Barnes & Noble Education Reports Second Quarter Fiscal Year 2019 Financial Results |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=December 4, 2018 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Barnes & Noble Education revealed that the company had turned down several offers by California-based Bay Capital Finance to take over the company citing that the offers by Bay Capital were \"substantially undervalued BNED, were highly conditional and not credible.\"<ref name=\"forbes-2019jul28\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ellenduffer/2019/07/28/barnes--noble-education-declines-acquisition-offer/ |title=Barnes & Noble Education Declines Acquisition Offer |magazine=[[Forbes]] |date=July 28, 2019 |first=Ellen |last=Duffer}}</ref> Unlike its former parent company, BNED was diversifying its business by the acquisition of many digital services companies to increase the number of services offered by its Digital Student Solutions division during its past four years as an independent company.\n\n===Digital Student Solutions division===\nIn March 2016, Barnes & Noble Education enlarged their Digital Student Solutions online services division by acquiring LoudCloud Systems, a digital platform and analytics provider to clients in higher education, the for-profit sector, and K-12 segment.<ref name=\"bw-2016mar08\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20160308005868/en/Barnes-Noble-Education-Announces-Acquisition-LoudCloud-Systems |title=Barnes & Noble Education, Inc. Announces the Acquisition of LoudCloud Systems |work=[[Business Wire]] |date=March 8, 2016 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Barnes & Noble Education acquired Student Brands for $58.5 Million.<ref name=\"pw-2017aug07\">{{cite news |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/industry-deals/article/74428-b-n-education-buys-student-brands-for-58-5-million.html |title=B&N Education Buys Student Brands for $58.5 Million |newspaper=[[Publishers Weekly]] |date=August 7, 2017 |first=Jim |last=Milliot}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Barnes & Noble Education acquired PaperRater, a service that help students write papers and identify plagiarism.<ref name=\"marketwatch-2018aug22\">{{cite news |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/press-release/barnes-noble-education-acquires-paperratercom-2018-08-22 |title=Barnes & Noble Education Acquires PaperRater.com |website=[[MarketWatch]] |date=August 22, 2018 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Book Stacks Unlimited]]\n* [[Bookselling]]\n* [[List of book distributors]]\n* [[List of bookstore chains]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Books|Companies|New York City}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|author=Kirkpatrick, David D.|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/news/bizfinance/biz/features/47/ |title=Barnes & Noble's Jekyll and Hyde|magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York magazine]] |date= July 19, 1999}}\n* {{cite news|author=Trachtenberg, Jeffrey A.|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303626804579507321532982730?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10001424052702303626804579507321532982730.html |title=What's Barnes & Noble's Survival Plan? Former CEO Cuts Holding to 20%, but Says, 'The Story Isn't Written Yet'|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= April 18, 2014|url-access=subscription}}\n* {{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iuct6UkKs7o|title=The Rise And Fall Of Barnes & Noble|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2018-11-08}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Barnes & Noble}}\n* {{official website}}\n* [http://www.secdatabase.com/CIK/890491/Company-Name/BARNES-%26-NOBLE-INC Barnes & Noble SEC Filing]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101101215022/http://mainstore.bncollege.com/ Barnes & Noble at 18th Street Bookstore (flagship store)]\n\n{{Bookstore Chains}}\n{{ebooks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes and Noble}}\n[[Category:Barnes & Noble| ]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2019 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1917]]\n[[Category:Book selling websites]]\n[[Category:Bookstores established in the 20th century]]\n[[Category:Bookstores in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Bookstores of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:E-book suppliers]]\n[[Category:Music retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Online retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Private equity portfolio companies]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Retai